    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT correct regarding the classification of medicines?**",
    "text": "The Human Medicines Regulations 2012 regulates the authorisation, sale and supply of medicinal products for human use.",
    "why": "d) Pharmacy medicines can only be sold by the responsible pharmacist.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nPharmacy (P) medicines do not need to be sold exclusively by the responsible pharmacist. They can be sold by appropriately trained pharmacy staff (e.g., pharmacy assistants or dispensers with qualifications such as NVQ Level 2 or equivalent) under the supervision of the responsible pharmacist. This ensures safe and appropriate supply while allowing the pharmacist to oversee other duties within the pharmacy.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) General sale medicines are self-selection of medicines in registered pharmacies.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. General Sale List (GSL) medicines are available for self-selection in registered pharmacies and other approved retail outlets.\r\n\r\nb) General sale medicines can be sold in retail outlets.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. GSL medicines can be sold outside of pharmacies in general retail outlets such as supermarkets, provided the packaging remains intact, and the sale complies with relevant regulations.\r\n\r\nc) General sale medicines can be sold whilst the responsible pharmacist is physically absent for a limited time period whilst remaining responsible.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. GSL medicines can be sold in a registered pharmacy even when the responsible pharmacist is temporarily absent, provided appropriate procedures are in place.\r\n\r\nd) Pharmacy medicines can only be sold by the responsible pharmacist.\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Pharmacy medicines can be sold by trained pharmacy staff under the supervision of the responsible pharmacist. The responsible pharmacist does not need to sell them personally.\r\n\r\ne) Pharmacy medicines must not be accessible for self-selection.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Pharmacy (P) medicines must not be openly accessible for customers to select themselves. They must be stored in a manner that requires staff intervention to supply them.\r\n\r\nKey Points About the Classification of Medicines\r\n\r\nGeneral Sale List (GSL) Medicines:\r\n\r\nCan be sold in retail outlets, including supermarkets, and are available for self-selection.\r\nMay also be sold in pharmacies even in the temporary absence of the responsible pharmacist.\r\nPharmacy (P) Medicines:\r\n\r\nOnly available in registered pharmacies.\r\nMust be supplied under the supervision of the responsible pharmacist.\r\nCannot be self-selected by customers and must be stored behind the counter or in a restricted area.\r\nPrescription Only Medicines (POMs):\r\n\r\nRequire a valid prescription for supply.\r\nMust be dispensed by a pharmacist or under their direct supervision.\r\n\r\nThe Human Medicines Regulations 2012 define the rules for classifying and selling medicines to ensure safe and appropriate supply. General Sale List (GSL) medicines can be sold in retail outlets or pharmacies and are available for self-selection. Pharmacy (P) medicines, however, require supervision by the responsible pharmacist but can be supplied by trained staff, ensuring compliance without requiring the pharmacist to sell them personally. Clear differentiation between GSL, P, and Prescription Only Medicines (POMs) is essential for maintaining patient safety and adherence to legal requirements.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
