    "text": "A parent comes in to your pharmacy and tells you that some of her family has contracted scabies. She wishes to buy some permethrin 5%w/v cream which was recommended to her. You question her further and find she is looking for treatment of a 2 year old, a 4 year old, one 9 year old and an adult who is a normal size.\u00a0\r\nThe SmPC for permethrin has been provided for this question. \r\n[SmPC for Permethrin](https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/product/6540/smpc#gref)",
    "why": "b) 60 grams\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe Summary of Product Characteristics (SmPC) for permethrin 5% w/v cream provides specific guidance on the amount required by age group for treating scabies:\r\n\r\n2-year-old: 7.5 grams\r\n4-year-old: 7.5 grams\r\n9-year-old: 15 grams\r\nAdult: 30 grams\r\nAdding these quantities results in a total requirement of 60 grams. Therefore, 60 grams of permethrin cream should be supplied for the treatment of this family.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\na) 30 grams: This amount would be insufficient for the entire family, covering only the adult treatment.\r\nc) 75 grams: While slightly over the requirement, this is more than needed according to the SmPC.\r\nd) 120 grams: This exceeds the calculated amount by double, making it unnecessary and wasteful.\r\ne) 150 grams: This is even more excessive, given the specific amounts needed for effective treatment.\r\n\r\n\r\nScabies is a contagious skin condition caused by the Sarcoptes scabiei mite, resulting in intense itching and a pimple-like rash. Permethrin 5% w/v cream is the first-line treatment recommended by NICE for scabies due to its high efficacy and safety profile.\r\n\r\nApplication: Apply the cream to the entire body, including under the nails, avoiding the face and eyes. Leave it on for 8\u201312 hours (usually overnight).\r\nDosage by Age: NICE guidelines and the SmPC specify age-adjusted quantities, as seen in the posology table provided in the SmPC. These quantities help ensure complete coverage and effectiveness.\r\n\r\nRepeat Treatment: Treatment should be repeated after 7 days to eliminate any newly hatched mites.\r\nClose Contacts: All close contacts should be treated simultaneously to prevent re-infestation, even if they show no symptoms.\r\nRegular monitoring for symptom improvement and educating patients on the importance of applying the cream thoroughly is essential to achieving effective treatment outcomes.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 5 (Infestations):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
