    "title": "**Which of the following is the LEAST appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 33 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy with irritable bowel syndrome. She would like some dietary and lifestyle advice.",
    "why": "The least appropriate advice for the patient is:\r\n\r\nEat 5 portions of fruit per day, each portion should be 80g.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nWhile a balanced diet is important for overall health, individuals with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) should be cautious with their fruit intake. Eating too much fruit, especially certain types, can exacerbate IBS symptoms like bloating, gas, and diarrhoea due to the fructose content. NICE guidelines recommend that patients with IBS limit their fruit intake to no more than 3 portions per day, as excess fruit consumption may worsen symptoms.\r\n\r\nAvoid missing meals or leaving long gaps between meals is appropriate advice, as regular meals can help regulate bowel function and reduce IBS flare-ups.\r\nEnsure adequate hydration by drinking at least 8 cups of fluid per day is essential for maintaining digestive health and preventing constipation, a common symptom in IBS.\r\nIf suffering from diarrhoea, avoid sorbitol due to its laxative properties is also appropriate advice, as sorbitol, a sugar alcohol found in some fruits and sugar-free products, can aggravate diarrhoea in IBS patients.\r\nReduce intake of alcohol and fizzy drinks is recommended because both can trigger or worsen IBS symptoms.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance on Dietary and Lifestyle Management for IBS\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines suggest the following strategies for managing IBS through diet and lifestyle:\r\n\r\nRegular Eating Patterns: Patients should be advised to eat meals at regular intervals and avoid skipping meals, as consistent eating patterns can help regulate bowel habits.\r\n\r\nHydration: Drinking plenty of water, at least 8 cups a day, is important, especially for those experiencing constipation. However, caffeine intake should be limited to avoid exacerbating symptoms.\r\n\r\nFruit and Fibre Intake: Patients should limit fruit consumption to no more than 3 portions per day and may need to experiment with soluble fibre (e.g., oats, linseeds) while reducing insoluble fibre (e.g., bran) to identify what works best for their symptoms.\r\n\r\nAvoiding Common Triggers: Alcohol, fizzy drinks, and foods containing sorbitol or other artificial sweeteners should be limited or avoided, especially in patients who experience diarrhoea as part of their symptoms.\r\n\r\nAdditional Insights\r\n\r\nIBS is a chronic and often unpredictable condition that can be managed effectively with dietary and lifestyle modifications. Each individual may have different triggers, so it is important to offer personalised advice and encourage patients to keep a food and symptom diary. This can help identify specific foods that worsen symptoms and enable tailored dietary adjustments.\r\n\r\nPatients should also be educated about the low FODMAP diet, which involves reducing fermentable carbohydrates to alleviate symptoms like bloating and abdominal pain. However, such dietary changes should ideally be implemented under the guidance of a healthcare professional. If symptoms persist or worsen despite these changes, a referral to a GP or dietitian for further evaluation and personalised advice may be necessary.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson chapter 7 Gastroenterology:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
