    "id": 2620,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 52 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy requesting advice for her husband with a headache. She informs his headaches are severe intense pain at the back of the head. He also explains he has been vomiting with the pain.",
    "why": "This is an emergency situation and this could be a subarachnoid haemorrhage, although very rare you will come across this in clinical practice as many patients are either unconscious or conscious without any awareness. Additionally anyone over the age of 50 with a new onset of severe headache is a red flag referral.\r\n\r\n- **Main Symptoms of Subarachnoid Haemorrhage**:\r\n  - Sudden severe headache (\"thunderclap\" headache)\r\n  - Stiff neck\r\n  - Nausea and vomiting\r\n  - Sensitivity to light (photophobia)\r\n  - Blurred or double vision\r\n  - Stroke-like symptoms (slurred speech, weakness on one side)\r\n  - Loss of consciousness or convulsions (seizures)\r\n  \r\n- **Immediate Action**: A subarachnoid haemorrhage is a medical emergency. Call 999 for an ambulance if these symptoms occur.\r\n\r\n- **Diagnosis & Treatment**:\r\n  - CT scan to confirm bleeding.\r\n  - Transfer to a specialist neuroscience unit.\r\n  - Medications to prevent complications.\r\n  - Procedure to repair the bleeding source.\r\n\r\n- **Causes**:\r\n  - Often caused by a ruptured brain aneurysm.\r\n  - Risk factors: smoking, high blood pressure, excessive alcohol.\r\n  - Traumatic subarachnoid haemorrhage can occur due to severe head injuries.\r\n\r\n- **Affected Individuals**:\r\n  - Common in ages 45-70.\r\n  - More common in women and black individuals, partly due to high blood pressure prevalence.\r\n\r\n- **Risk Reduction**:\r\n  - Quit smoking.\r\n  - Limit alcohol consumption.\r\n  - Manage blood pressure (exercise, healthy diet, weight control).\r\n\r\n- **Complications**:\r\n  - Short-term: further bleeding, brain damage.\r\n  - Long-term: epilepsy, memory issues, mood changes (e.g., depression).\r\n\r\n- **Outlook**:\r\n  - Recovery can be slow, with possible long-term issues like fatigue, headaches, and sleep problems.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on Chapter 4 Neurology (Headaches and migraines):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
