    "text": "A 72 year old patient presents to the pharmacy with constipation. Upon questioning, you suspect medicine induced constipation.",
    "why": "Carbamazepine\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nCarbamazepine is an anticonvulsant and mood-stabilizing medication that has anticholinergic effects, which can lead to constipation. While lercanidipine, a calcium channel blocker, can also contribute to constipation, carbamazepine is more commonly recognized in this context due to its side effect profile.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nLisinopril: This medication, an ACE inhibitor, is generally not associated with constipation.\r\n\r\nLercanidipine: While it may cause constipation, it is less frequently reported compared to carbamazepine in clinical settings.\r\n\r\nMetformin: This drug is primarily associated with gastrointestinal side effects like diarrhea rather than constipation.\r\n\r\nRivastigmine: Although it may cause gastrointestinal upset, constipation is not a typical side effect.\r\n\r\n\r\nConstipation is a common condition in older adults, particularly when medication regimens include drugs that impact bowel motility. NICE guidelines suggest that healthcare providers should carefully assess medications known to cause constipation, particularly in vulnerable populations. Anticholinergic medications, opioids, and certain antiepileptics, like carbamazepine, are notable for their potential to induce constipation. Appropriate management includes reviewing medications, advising on dietary changes, and ensuring adequate fluid intake to alleviate symptoms effectively.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
