    "title": "**What is the most likely cause of his toenail problem?**",
    "text": "A 45-year-old man comes to the pharmacy with a complaint of thickened and discoloured toenails. He says he has been wearing tight shoes for work and often has sweaty feet. He has no other medical conditions or allergies. He shows you a picture of his toenails on his phone.\r\n\r\n![fungalnail](https://i.ibb.co/Sf14R2S/fungalnail.jpg \"650x500\")",
    "why": "Fungal nail infection\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe most likely cause of this patient's toenail problem is fungal nail infection (onychomycosis). Thickened, discoloured nails are typical signs of a fungal infection, especially in individuals who wear tight shoes and have sweaty feet. These conditions create a moist environment conducive to fungal growth. Fungal infections commonly affect toenails and can lead to a yellow, white, or brown discolouration, thickening, and crumbling of the nail.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nLichen planus: This is a chronic inflammatory condition that can affect the skin, hair, nails, and mucous membranes. In nail involvement, it may cause nail thinning, splitting, or ridging rather than the thickening and discolouration seen with fungal infections. It is less likely in this case given the patient's description and history.\r\n\r\nMelanoma: Subungual melanoma may cause dark streaks or pigmentation changes under the nail, but it does not typically lead to thickening and is less common compared to fungal infections. Melanoma should be considered if there is a new dark patch or streak under the nail, but this does not seem to match the patient\u2019s description.\r\n\r\nPsoriasis: Psoriatic nail disease can cause pitting, thickening, or separation of the nail from the nail bed. However, psoriasis tends to affect the skin as well, and without a history of psoriatic skin lesions, it is less likely to be the cause in this scenario.\r\n\r\nTrauma: Repeated trauma from tight shoes can cause nail thickening or discolouration, but the patient\u2019s complaint of thickened, discoloured nails, coupled with a history of wearing tight shoes and sweating, is more indicative of a fungal infection.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, fungal nail infections (onychomycosis) are common, particularly in people with risk factors like wearing tight shoes, having sweaty feet, or experiencing trauma to the nail. Diagnosis is usually clinical, based on nail appearance, but confirmation through nail clippings or scrapings for mycology may be required. First-line treatment includes topical antifungals (e.g., amorolfine) for mild infections, or oral antifungals like terbinafine for more severe or extensive infections. Proper foot hygiene, keeping nails dry, and wearing well-fitting shoes are recommended preventive measures.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
