    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most likely cause of her symptoms?**",
    "text": "A 22-year-old woman visits the pharmacy with a rash on her face and body. She says she has been feeling unwell for the last few days with a headache, sore throat, and swollen glands. She has no other medical conditions or allergies. She shows you a picture of her rash on her phone.\r\n\r\n![rubella](https://i.ibb.co/Tbywc9M/rubella.jpg \"500x500\")",
    "why": "d) Rubella\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nRubella, also known as German measles, typically presents with a rash that begins on the face and spreads to the body. Common accompanying symptoms include mild fever, headache, sore throat, and swollen glands, particularly behind the ears (posterior auricular lymphadenopathy). The symptoms described by the patient and the rash\u2019s appearance and progression align closely with rubella.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\na) Allergic reaction: While allergic reactions can cause rashes, they are usually not accompanied by systemic symptoms like swollen glands or fever.\r\nb) Chickenpox: The chickenpox rash typically consists of itchy, fluid-filled blisters that crust over, usually starting on the torso before spreading. This does not match the description of the rash or symptoms in this case.\r\nc) Measles: Measles can cause a similar rash, but it usually includes additional symptoms like Koplik spots in the mouth, severe cough, and conjunctivitis, which are not reported by the patient.\r\ne) Scarlet fever: The rash of scarlet fever typically feels rough (like sandpaper) and is often accompanied by a red, \"strawberry\" tongue and a history of sore throat caused by Streptococcus infection, which does not align with this patient\u2019s presentation.\r\n\r\nRubella is a mild, contagious viral infection caused by the rubella virus, presenting with a distinctive red or pink rash, low-grade fever, headache, and swollen lymph nodes. The rash typically starts on the face and spreads to the trunk and limbs. Symptoms are usually mild, but rubella can be particularly dangerous during pregnancy as it may cause congenital rubella syndrome, resulting in severe birth defects.\r\n\r\n\r\nTransmission: Rubella spreads through respiratory droplets, so isolation during the infectious period (usually 7 days before and after rash onset) is advised to prevent transmission.\r\nVaccination: The MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccine is effective in preventing rubella and is part of the routine immunisation schedule.\r\nManagement: Generally, rubella is self-limiting, and treatment focuses on relieving symptoms, such as using antipyretics for fever.\r\nPublic Health: Notification of suspected cases to public health authorities is necessary to control outbreaks and prevent complications in vulnerable populations, especially pregnant women.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 1 (paediatrics):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
