    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 22 year old male patient presents to the pharmacy with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) . He was diagnosed with IBS six months ago and has been adhering to the dietary advice his GP gave him.\u00a0\r\nHe informs you despite adhering to dietary advice, he is still suffering with constipation.",
    "why": "Suggest a bulk-forming laxative to produce regular, soft, well-formed stool.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor patients with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) who suffer from constipation, NICE recommends dietary and lifestyle interventions as first-line treatment, such as increasing fibre intake (with soluble fibre preferred over insoluble fibre) and ensuring adequate fluid intake. However, when these measures are insufficient, the next step is to consider pharmacological treatment.\r\n\r\nBulk-forming laxatives are the first-line pharmacological treatment for constipation in IBS. They help form regular, soft, well-formed stools and are generally well-tolerated, making them an effective and appropriate option for managing constipation in IBS. NICE advises avoiding stimulant or osmotic laxatives, such as lactulose, as they may cause bloating and discomfort in IBS patients.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nLinaclotide is reserved for patients with severe IBS with constipation who have not responded to laxatives or other treatments. Referral to a gastroenterologist is also not needed at this stage.\r\nReinforcing dietary advice is important but insufficient as the patient is already following such advice without improvement.\r\nLactulose is not recommended due to its potential to worsen bloating and abdominal discomfort in IBS patients.\r\nIrritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS) is a common gastrointestinal disorder characterised by symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, and altered bowel habits, including constipation and/or diarrhoea. \r\n\r\nThe management of IBS begins with dietary and lifestyle modifications, emphasising the importance of a balanced diet and adequate fluid intake. Patients are often advised to increase their intake of soluble fibre while avoiding high-fat and high-sugar foods, which can exacerbate symptoms. If dietary changes alone do not alleviate symptoms, NICE recommends the use of bulk-forming laxatives as a first-line treatment for constipation-predominant IBS, helping to produce regular and well-formed stools. For those with more severe symptoms or those who do not respond to initial treatments, further options may include prescription medications or referrals for additional support.            \r\nRegular follow-up is important to tailor management strategies and address any new or worsening symptoms.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
