    "text": "A 42 year old female presents to the pharmacy with diarrhoea and bloating for the past 3 weeks. She informs you her stools are frothy and often float on the toilet. She also informs you she has been feeling very tired.",
    "why": "Malabsorption syndrome\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe symptoms of frothy, floating stools, bloating, diarrhoea for 3 weeks, and feeling very tired suggest malabsorption syndrome. Frothy stools that float indicate the presence of fat, a sign of fat malabsorption, which is characteristic of conditions like coeliac disease or chronic pancreatitis. Tiredness can be due to nutrient deficiencies caused by poor absorption of vitamins and minerals.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nCrohn's disease: While Crohn's disease can cause diarrhoea and fatigue, the hallmark symptoms typically include abdominal pain and sometimes bloody stools. Crohn\u2019s can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract, but fat malabsorption and frothy stools are more specific to malabsorption syndromes.\r\n\r\nColorectal cancer: Colorectal cancer can present with changes in bowel habits, blood in the stool, and weight loss, but frothy, floating stools are not typical. Fatigue may occur due to anaemia or other systemic effects, but the presentation here points more to malabsorption.\r\n\r\nGastro-enteritis: This would generally present with acute diarrhoea, vomiting, and possibly fever, but it is usually short-lived and resolves within a week or two. The chronic nature of the symptoms here suggests a longer-term condition like malabsorption syndrome.\r\n\r\nUlcerative colitis: Ulcerative colitis causes bloody diarrhoea and urgency but not typically frothy or fatty stools. The lack of abdominal pain and the nature of the stools make this less likely.\r\n\r\nMalabsorption syndromes involve the improper absorption of nutrients in the gastrointestinal tract. Common causes include coeliac disease, chronic pancreatitis, and small bowel bacterial overgrowth. Symptoms include diarrhoea, bloating, fatigue, and steatorrhoea (fatty stools). NICE guidelines recommend evaluating patients with chronic diarrhoea, unexplained weight loss, and signs of malnutrition for potential malabsorption. Diagnosis is often made via blood tests for nutritional deficiencies, stool tests for fat content, and possibly endoscopy or biopsy for underlying conditions like coeliac disease. Treatment focuses on managing the underlying cause and supplementing deficient nutrients.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
