    "id": 2493,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**The patient asks why the prescription is only for a 30-day supply. What is the most appropriate response?**",
    "text": "A female patient who wears contact lenses and has been initiated on isotretinoin. Their blood test results are shown below:\r\n\r\nLDL 1.9 mmol/L (<3mmol/L)\r\nALT 42 units/L (7 \u2013 56 units/L)\r\nTotal bilirubin 0.7 mg/dL (0.3 - 1.9 mg/dL)",
    "why": "E. To ensure the patient is not pregnant whilst taking the drug.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nIsotretinoin is a highly teratogenic drug, meaning it poses a significant risk of severe birth defects if taken during pregnancy. For this reason, strict measures are in place to ensure that women of childbearing potential do not conceive while taking isotretinoin. The Pregnancy Prevention Programme (PPP) mandates that:\r\n\r\nWomen of childbearing potential must have monthly negative pregnancy tests before receiving a new supply.\r\n\r\nPrescriptions for isotretinoin must be limited to a maximum of 30 days to align with these tests and prevent overuse or misuse.\r\n\r\nA. It is routine to supply prescriptions for one month to reduce wastage (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nWhile reducing wastage is a valid pharmacy practice, it is not the primary reason for restricting isotretinoin supplies to a 30-day limit.\r\n\r\nB. To allow for closer monitoring of interacting medicines (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nAlthough isotretinoin has potential drug interactions (e.g., with tetracyclines or vitamin A), the 30-day restriction is specifically linked to the PPP, not to monitoring of drug interactions.\r\n\r\nC. To allow for monthly blood tests and adjust the dose if needed (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nMonitoring blood tests (e.g., lipid profile and liver function tests) is essential during isotretinoin therapy, but the frequency of testing varies by clinical need and is not necessarily tied to the monthly prescription limit.\r\n\r\nD. To ensure good overall adherence with the therapy (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nAlthough adherence is a general goal in any treatment, it is not the rationale for limiting isotretinoin prescriptions to a 30-day supply.\r\n\r\nE. To ensure the patient is not pregnant whilst taking the drug (Correct):\r\n\r\nThe monthly supply restriction ensures that pregnancy tests can be performed regularly and that the patient has ongoing access to contraception, both essential components of the PPP.\r\n\r\nIsotretinoin prescriptions are limited to a 30-day supply for women of childbearing potential due to the Pregnancy Prevention Programme (PPP). This programme aims to minimise the risk of pregnancy during isotretinoin therapy through monthly negative pregnancy tests and strict adherence to contraception.\r\n\r\nAdditional monitoring, such as liver function tests and lipid profiles, is conducted during therapy but does not directly determine the prescription duration. By enforcing these measures, healthcare providers help mitigate the significant risks of isotretinoin-associated teratogenicity.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
