    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?\u00a0**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription for a 49-year-old female. She is currently in your community pharmacy and you notice that she is getting more aggressive and inpatient whilst she waits in the pharmacy.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\n\r\n![4](https://i.ibb.co/KKDthhV/4.png)",
    "why": "(a) Call the police immediately\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe correct response is to call the police immediately. The NHS England guidelines advise pharmacists not to dispense potentially suspicious prescriptions under these circumstances, especially if a patient becomes aggressive. Pharmacists are advised to stall for time and verify the prescription with the prescriber using a verified, published contact number\u2014not the number listed on the prescription itself, which could be falsified.\r\n\r\nIf the patient remains in the pharmacy and becomes aggressive or poses a potential threat, calling 999 is essential to ensure the safety of staff and other customers. Additionally, pharmacists should notify NHS England and the NHS Counter Fraud Authority to report the incident, allowing further investigation and monitoring of potentially fraudulent or unsafe prescriptions.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(b) Call the prescriber using the number on the prescription \u2013 Using the number on the prescription is discouraged as it may not be legitimate. NHS England recommends using a verified, public number.\r\n\r\n(c) Dispense both amoxicillin and diazepam \u2013 Dispensing the medication without verification may be unsafe, especially given the aggressive behavior and potential risk of misuse with diazepam, a controlled drug.\r\n\r\n(d) Dispense amoxicillin only \u2013 Partial dispensing without verification is also inappropriate in a suspicious scenario.\r\n\r\n(e) Tell her the medicine is not in stock and give the prescription back \u2013 This may not resolve the situation and could increase the potential for conflict without addressing safety concerns.\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen faced with a potentially aggressive patient presenting a prescription that includes controlled substances like diazepam, pharmacists are advised to prioritise safety and adhere to NHS England guidance. This includes refraining from dispensing the medication, verifying the prescriber's details using an official contact, and notifying the police if necessary. Reporting incidents to NHS England and NHS Counter Fraud Authority is crucial for broader monitoring and preventing prescription fraud or misuse.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information:\u00a0\r\n\r\nWatch MEP lesson on Chapter 1 ( Core concepts and skills)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep\r\n\r\nhttps://www.england.nhs.uk/south/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2021/08/2021-22-forged-prescriptions-guidance.pdf",
