    "why": "c) 12 years and over\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nClobetasone 0.05% cream is a mild-to-moderate potency steroid and is one of the few corticosteroids that can be sold over the counter (OTC) for treating skin conditions such as eczema and dermatitis. According to OTC regulations, clobetasone 0.05% should only be used in individuals aged 12 years and over for safe and effective management of mild to moderate inflammatory skin conditions. For younger children, steroid creams should be prescribed by a healthcare provider to ensure appropriate use and monitoring due to the potential for skin thinning and other side effects with improper use.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Options\r\n\r\na) 8 years and over\r\n\r\nIncorrect. Clobetasone 0.05% is not approved for OTC use in children under 12 due to safety considerations, such as a higher risk of skin atrophy in younger skin.\r\n\r\nb) 10 years and over\r\n\r\nIncorrect. Although the lower age threshold for some medications may be set at 10 years, clobetasone is restricted to individuals aged 12 and over for OTC sales.\r\n\r\nc) 12 years and over\r\n\r\nCorrect. Clobetasone 0.05% can be sold OTC for patients aged 12 years and above, making this the correct answer.\r\n\r\nd) 15 years and over\r\n\r\nIncorrect. While certain medications might restrict use to 15 years and above, clobetasone is safe to use in patients 12 years and older when used correctly.\r\n\r\ne) 18 years and over\r\n\r\nIncorrect. Clobetasone 0.05% does not have an age restriction of 18 for OTC sales; the correct age limit for OTC use is 12 years and over.\r\nSummary of Steroid Cream Usage According to NICE Guidelines\r\nSteroid creams are commonly used for managing inflammatory skin conditions such as eczema and dermatitis. According to NICE guidelines, low-to-moderate potency corticosteroids like clobetasone can be recommended for short-term use to reduce inflammation and symptoms. For OTC use, clobetasone 0.05% is limited to individuals aged 12 years and over. It is important to advise patients to follow application guidelines to avoid potential side effects, including skin thinning and irritation, particularly when used on delicate areas or for extended periods.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
