    "why": "Angular cheilitis\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nThe most likely diagnosis is angular cheilitis, which causes red, sore fissures at the corners (angles) of the mouth. It can result from a fungal or bacterial infection, nutritional deficiencies (such as vitamin B12 or iron deficiency), or mechanical irritation, such as licking the lips or wearing poorly fitted dentures. It is commonly associated with Candida or Staphylococcus aureus infections, and treatment may involve anti-fungal or antibacterial medication, as well as improving oral hygiene.\r\n\r\nThe other options are less likely because:\r\n\r\nAphthous ulcers (mouth ulcers) occur inside the mouth, not at the corners. Minor aphthous ulcers are less than 1 cm in size and can appear singly or in clusters of up to 5. Major aphthous ulcers are larger than 1 cm and can appear in numbers up to 10 at a time.\r\nDermatitis around the mouth (perioral dermatitis) usually appears as acne-like red bumps on the lower half of the face, rather than isolated soreness at the corners of the mouth.\r\nHerpes simplex (cold sores - HSV 1) typically begins as a tingling sensation on the lip, progressing to a fluid-filled blister that later crusts over. It usually does not cause fissures at the corners of the mouth.\r\nImpetigo is common in children but can affect adults as well. It is caused by Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus pyogenes. Impetigo starts as a red rash with vesicles around the nose and mouth, which ooze and form a distinctive \"golden crust.\" It does not typically present as soreness limited to the corners of the mouth.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, angular cheilitis is often linked to Candida or Staphylococcus aureus infection, with contributing factors such as drooling, lip licking, or wearing dentures. Treatment should target the underlying cause, whether it is an infection, a nutritional deficiency, or mechanical irritation. Using barrier creams or emollients can protect the area from further irritation. Referral is advised for recurrent or severe cases, which may require more comprehensive investigation and treatment.**Image reference: DermNetnz.org**\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
