    "why": "He should see his GP as soon as possible for antibiotic treatment\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe patient presents with acute watery diarrhoea after recent travel to Indonesia, which raises concern for traveller's diarrhoea, likely caused by bacterial or parasitic infection (such as E. coli, Salmonella, or Giardia). Traveller\u2019s diarrhoea is typically treated with antibiotics, particularly if the symptoms last more than a couple of days or involve severe dehydration. Given the prolonged symptoms and the travel history, a GP visit is important for appropriate testing and management, which may include antibiotics depending on the cause.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nHe is experiencing a side effect of levetiracetam: While levetiracetam can cause gastrointestinal side effects, diarrhoea is uncommon, and acute onset following travel makes infection a more likely cause.\r\n\r\nHis symptoms are viral in origin and therefore self-limiting: Although viral causes of diarrhoea are possible, the recent travel history increases the likelihood of bacterial or parasitic infection, which might require specific treatment like antibiotics.\r\n\r\nStop taking levetiracetam straight away and see his GP: There is no indication that the diarrhoea is related to levetiracetam, and stopping it suddenly could risk worsening seizure control. Therefore, stopping the medication without consulting a GP would not be appropriate.\r\n\r\nSell loperamide 2mg capsules for symptomatic treatment: Loperamide can be useful for symptom relief in uncomplicated diarrhoea, but it is not recommended for traveller\u2019s diarrhoea caused by bacterial infections, as it can prolong the illness by trapping the bacteria in the intestines. Proper evaluation and antibiotic treatment are more appropriate in this case.\r\n\r\nTraveller\u2019s diarrhoea is a common condition for people returning from areas with lower sanitation standards. It is often caused by bacterial infections (most commonly E. coli) but can also be viral or parasitic. NICE recommends that patients with diarrhoea lasting more than 3 days, or those with severe symptoms (e.g., fever, blood in stool, dehydration), should seek medical attention for possible antibiotic treatment. For less severe cases, hydration and self-care measures may be sufficient. Anti-motility agents like loperamide should be used with caution and only in uncomplicated cases, as they may worsen bacterial infections.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
