    "title": "**Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's symptoms?**",
    "text": "A 42 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy regarding a problem with her mouth.\u00a0\r\nA picture of the patient\u2019s mouth is presented below:\r\n![mouth-ulcer](https://i.ibb.co/YTrk83d/mouth-ulcer.jpg \"650x500\")",
    "why": "The most likely cause of the patient\u2019s symptoms is:\r\n\r\nMinor aphthous ulcer.\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nMinor aphthous ulcers are the most common type of mouth ulcer. They usually appear as small, round or oval sores with a white or yellow centre and a red border. These ulcers are generally less than 1 cm in diameter, occur on the non-keratinised mucosa (such as the inside of the lips, cheeks, or under the tongue), and heal within 1\u20132 weeks without scarring. The description and the typical location of the ulcer in the patient\u2019s mouth match these characteristics.\r\n\r\nMajor aphthous ulcers are larger (greater than 1 cm), deeper, and can take several weeks to heal, often leaving scars.\r\nMedicine-induced ulcers are typically associated with medications such as NSAIDs or chemotherapeutic agents. If the patient had a relevant medication history, this would be considered.\r\n\r\nHerpetiform ulcers are multiple tiny ulcers that may fuse together, unlike the single ulcer observed.\r\nOral carcinoma often presents as a persistent, non-healing sore or ulcer with indurated (hard) edges, which does not match the appearance of a minor aphthous ulcer.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance on Management of Minor Aphthous Ulcers\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, the management of minor aphthous ulcers includes:\r\n\r\nTopical Analgesics: Application of topical anaesthetics like lidocaine gel can provide temporary pain relief.\r\n\r\nAntiseptic Mouthwashes: Using chlorhexidine mouthwash may reduce bacterial growth and promote healing, although it may not alleviate pain.\r\n\r\nTopical Steroids: Hydrocortisone buccal tablets or other mild corticosteroids can be used to reduce inflammation and promote healing if symptoms are severe.\r\n\r\nDiet and Irritant Avoidance: Advising the patient to avoid spicy, acidic, or rough-textured foods that may aggravate the ulcer can help minimise discomfort.\r\n\r\nAdditional Insights\r\n\r\nMinor aphthous ulcers are usually self-limiting and often do not require specific medical treatment beyond symptom management. Stress, hormonal changes, or minor trauma (e.g., biting the inside of the cheek) are common triggers for these ulcers. While they are generally harmless, recurrent episodes may warrant further investigation to rule out underlying systemic conditions like nutrient deficiencies (e.g., iron, vitamin B12) or gastrointestinal disorders (e.g., coeliac disease).\r\n\r\nEducating patients on good oral hygiene and the importance of a balanced diet can also help in preventing recurrence. If the ulcer persists beyond two weeks or if the patient experiences recurrent episodes with severe symptoms, referral to a GP or dentist for further evaluation may be necessary to rule out other causes.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson on Chapter 8 Dermatology:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
