    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "A pharmacist independent prescriber is considering prescribing a controlled drug for a patient with chronic pain.",
    "text": "**Theme: Controlled drug prescribing**\r\n**Instruction: For each of the scenarios below, select the most appropriate answer option from the list above. Each option may be used once, more than once, or not at all.**",
    "why": "F. Schedules 2-5 for any medical condition within their competence, except diamorphine, cocaine, and dipipanone for the treatment of addiction\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPharmacist independent prescribers are permitted to prescribe controlled drugs in Schedules 2-5 for any medical condition within their competence, except for diamorphine, cocaine, and dipipanone if the purpose is treating addiction. However, these drugs can be prescribed for other conditions, such as chronic pain management or palliative care, provided that the prescriber is competent to manage the patient\u2019s condition and the treatment falls within their scope of practice.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA. Cannot prescribe controlled drugs in Schedules 2-5\r\nIncorrect. Pharmacist independent prescribers have broader prescribing rights and can prescribe controlled drugs from Schedules 2-5, with certain restrictions.\r\n\r\nB. Can only prescribe oral diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, and dihydrocodeine\r\nIncorrect. This restriction applies to podiatrist independent prescribers. Pharmacists have a broader range of controlled drugs they can prescribe.\r\n\r\nC. Can only prescribe oral diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, dihydrocodeine, oxycodone, IV and oral morphine, and fentanyl patches\r\nIncorrect. Pharmacist prescribers are not limited to these specific drugs and can prescribe across Schedules 2-5 for appropriate conditions within their competence.\r\n\r\nD. Can prescribe Schedules 2-5 controlled drugs and does not need a standardised form for private prescriptions for Schedules 2 and 3\r\nIncorrect. A standardised form is required for private prescriptions for Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs.\r\n\r\nE. Can prescribe any controlled drug listed in Schedules 2-5 for the treatment of addiction\r\nIncorrect. Pharmacists are restricted from prescribing diamorphine, cocaine, and dipipanone for addiction treatment, though these may be prescribed for other medical indications.\r\n\r\nG. Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs only\r\nIncorrect. Pharmacist independent prescribers can prescribe Schedules 2-5 within their professional scope and competence.\r\n\r\nH. Schedule 4 and 5 controlled medicines only\r\nIncorrect. This limitation does not apply to pharmacist independent prescribers, who may prescribe Schedules 2-5 with specified restrictions.\r\n\r\nUnder MEP guidelines, pharmacist independent prescribers have prescribing authority for controlled drugs in Schedules 2-5, excluding diamorphine, cocaine, and dipipanone when used for treating addiction. This authority is intended to provide appropriate access to controlled medications for the management of medical conditions such as chronic pain, while safeguarding against inappropriate prescribing for addiction. Pharmacists are expected to prescribe within their competence, ensuring patient safety and adherence to regulatory standards.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
