    "title": "**Which of the following antihistamines would be the most suitable?**",
    "text": "A mother presents to the pharmacy with her 18 month old daughter. Her daughter suffers from eczema and she is wondering if there is anything that can help with the itchiness.",
    "why": "Chlorphenamine\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe most suitable antihistamine for an 18-month-old child with eczema-related itchiness is chlorphenamine. It is one of the few antihistamines licensed for use in children under 2 years old. Chlorphenamine is a sedating antihistamine and is often used to help relieve itching and discomfort in children with skin conditions like eczema. The sedative effect can also be helpful for nighttime itching, allowing the child to sleep better.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nAcrivastine: This is a non-sedating antihistamine but is not licensed for use in children under 12 years old. It is not appropriate for an 18-month-old child.\r\n\r\nCetirizine: Although cetirizine is a non-sedating antihistamine that can be used for allergic reactions, it is typically licensed for children aged 2 years and older, making it unsuitable for this child.\r\n\r\nFexofenadine: Another non-sedating antihistamine, fexofenadine is only licensed for children 6 years and older, so it is not suitable for an 18-month-old.\r\n\r\nLoratadine: Loratadine is a non-sedating antihistamine used for allergic reactions, but it is usually recommended for children aged 2 years and older. Therefore, it is not the most appropriate choice for this child.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, sedating antihistamines, such as chlorphenamine, may be used in children to relieve symptoms of pruritus (itching) related to conditions like eczema. These are particularly useful for managing night-time symptoms that disrupt sleep. Non-sedating antihistamines (such as cetirizine and loratadine) are generally preferred for long-term use due to their minimal side effects, but they are not always licensed for children under 2 years old. Parents should be advised to use antihistamines under the guidance of healthcare professionals, and treatment should be accompanied by regular use of emollients to manage eczema effectively.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
