    "title": "**Which of the following is the LEAST appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A mother presents to the pharmacy with her 7 year old son. Her son suffers from atopic eczema and she has asked you if there is anything you could advise to help manage the condition.",
    "why": "Avoid applying emollients on moist skin (e.g. after a shower)\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nIt is incorrect to advise avoiding the application of emollients on moist skin. In fact, it is most effective to apply emollients immediately after bathing, while the skin is still damp. This practice helps to trap moisture and enhances the emollient's effectiveness at keeping the skin hydrated and preventing dryness. Applying emollients on dry skin is also beneficial, but applying them when the skin is slightly moist increases absorption and helps in managing the symptoms of atopic eczema.\r\n\r\nThe other options are appropriate because:\r\n\r\nAvoiding scratching with nails and using knuckles helps to reduce the risk of skin damage and infection.\r\nEmollients with a higher oil content, such as ointments, are more effective than creams in maintaining moisture and reducing water loss from the skin.\r\nAvoiding hot baths and showers is essential since hot water can exacerbate skin dryness by stripping the skin of its natural oils.\r\nFrequent application of emollients throughout the day is necessary to keep the skin moisturised, reduce irritation, and prevent flare-ups.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to the NICE guidelines, atopic eczema is a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterised by dryness, itching, and inflammation. The mainstay of treatment involves regular and liberal use of emollients to maintain skin hydration and improve the skin barrier function. Emollients should be applied immediately after bathing and as frequently as needed to keep the skin moisturised. During flare-ups, topical corticosteroids may be required to reduce inflammation. Patients are advised to avoid trigger factors such as hot water, harsh soaps, and excessive scratching. Maintaining a daily skin care routine with appropriate emollient use can significantly reduce the frequency and severity of eczema flare-ups.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
