    "id": 2498,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which one of the following activities CANNOT take place without a responsible pharmacist in charge of the pharmacy?**",
    "text": "You are the Responsible Pharmacist in your community pharmacy and you need to do a home visit for your care home patients. You expect to be absent for up to a maximum of two hours during the pharmacy business hours.",
    "why": "b) Emergency supply of a medicine(s) at the request of the patient\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nAn emergency supply of medicines at the request of a patient can only be authorised by the Responsible Pharmacist (RP). This is outlined under Regulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012. The RP must assess the immediate need for the prescription-only medicine, confirm impracticality of obtaining a prescription without undue delay, verify a prior prescription by a relevant prescriber, and determine the appropriate dose. This responsibility cannot be delegated or carried out in the absence of the RP as per the Responsible Pharmacist Regulations 2008.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Date checking\r\n\r\nThis is permissible in the absence of the Responsible Pharmacist as it does not involve patient-facing activities or decisions about the supply of medicines.\r\n\r\nc) Ordering stock from pharmaceutical wholesalers\r\n\r\nThis is an administrative activity that can take place during the absence of the Responsible Pharmacist. However, dispensing or supply-related tasks require the presence of the RP.\r\n\r\nd) Sale of general sale medicines\r\n\r\nGeneral Sale List (GSL) medicines can be sold in the absence of the Responsible Pharmacist provided the absence is within the two-hour limit and proper procedures are in place.\r\n\r\ne) Taking medicine off the dispensary shelves to assemble a prescription\r\n\r\nMedicines can be prepared for assembly in the absence of the Responsible Pharmacist. However, the final accuracy check and dispensing to the patient must only occur when the RP is present.\r\n\r\nKey Points About the Role of the Responsible Pharmacist\r\n\r\nEssential Tasks That Require the RP:\r\n\r\nAuthorisation of an emergency supply of medicines (patient or prescriber request).\r\nFinal accuracy check and supply of dispensed medicines.\r\nSupervising the sale or supply of Pharmacy (P) medicines.\r\n\r\nPermissible Activities During RP Absence:\r\n\r\nAdministrative tasks such as ordering stock or managing records.\r\nSale of General Sale List (GSL) medicines.\r\nNon-patient-facing activities like cleaning, maintenance, or date checking.\r\n\r\nAbsence Regulations:\r\n\r\nThe Responsible Pharmacist may be absent for up to two hours during operational hours but must remain contactable and ensure the pharmacy is appropriately staffed to manage safe operations.\r\n\r\nThe Responsible Pharmacist plays a crucial role in overseeing patient safety and medicine supply. While certain non-critical activities (e.g., stock ordering, GSL sales) can proceed during their absence, essential tasks like authorising emergency supplies of medicines require their direct involvement. Adherence to the Responsible Pharmacist Regulations ensures legal compliance and the continuity of safe pharmacy practice.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 4 (The Responsible Pharmacist)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
