    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the reason the prescription is legally invalid?**",
    "text": "You receive a veterinary prescription for a dashound called Rolls. However you realise you cannot dispense the prescription.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract has been provided for this question\u00a0\r\n![3](https://i.ibb.co/nMrVLr4/3.png \"600x400\")",
    "why": "(D) The statement of \u201cto be prescribed under the cascade is missing\u201d\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor a veterinary prescription to be legally valid when prescribing a medication not specifically licensed for the animal\u2019s species or condition, it must include the statement \u201cto be prescribed under the cascade.\u201d The cascade system allows veterinarians to prescribe medicines not licensed for certain animal use in specific circumstances, ensuring the treatment aligns with legal requirements for off-license use. The absence of this phrase renders the prescription legally invalid.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) No withdrawal period is stated:\r\nIncorrect. The withdrawal period is only mandatory for food-producing animals, like livestock, to ensure drug residues clear before consumption. Since Rolls is a dashound (non-food-producing animal), this information is not required.\r\n\r\n(B) Owner's date of birth is missing:\r\nIncorrect. Although the owner's name and address are necessary on a veterinary prescription, the date of birth is not a legal requirement.\r\n\r\n(C) The statement \u201cAnimal treatment only\u201d is missing:\r\nIncorrect. While \u201cAnimal treatment only\u201d is essential on the label of the dispensed medication, it is not required directly on the prescription for legal validity.\r\n\r\n(E) Veterinary prescriptions cannot be repeatable:\r\nIncorrect. Veterinary prescriptions can indeed be repeatable if the prescriber specifies repeats. For example, if noted as \u201crepeat 5 times,\u201d this means the prescription allows a total of six dispensations.\r\n\r\nThe veterinary \"cascade\" system is a regulatory framework that allows veterinarians to prescribe medications not specifically licensed for an animal's species or condition when no suitable licensed alternative is available. For any prescription issued under the cascade, it must legally include the statement \u201cto be prescribed under the cascade\u201d to ensure compliance. This phrase is essential when recommending an off-license or alternative treatment, providing clarity on the prescription's validity.\r\n\r\nThe cascade requires a hierarchy of choices: veterinarians should first use licensed medications for the specific species and condition, then consider medications licensed for other species or conditions, and only as a last resort, human medications. All veterinary prescriptions must also include the owner's name and address, the phrase \u201canimal treatment only,\u201d and full details of the medication. Withdrawal periods are only required for food-producing animals, and while the owner's name and address are necessary, their date of birth is not.\r\n\r\nPlease for more information watch the MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
