    "title": "**Which of the following actions is NOT appropriate for the pharmacist to take in order to investigate the validity of the prescription?**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription and suspect that it may be a forgery.",
    "why": "Correct Answer:\r\n\r\nD) Use the title \u2018Dr\u2019 before the signature to verify the authenticity of the prescription\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUsing a title such as \u201cDr\u201d before a signature is not a reliable or appropriate method of verifying a prescription. Titles can be easily written by anyone and are not unique identifiers of a prescriber. Verifying authenticity requires checking with the prescriber directly using independent contact details and reviewing the content and format of the prescription thoroughly.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Confirm details with the prescriber using contact details obtained from a source other than the suspicious prescription\r\n\r\nAppropriate \u2013 This is best practice. Always use an independent and trusted source (e.g. NHS website, practice contact details on record) to contact the prescriber when in doubt.\r\n\r\nB) Confirm whether or not a prescription has been issued, the original intention of the prescriber, and whether or not there has been an alteration\r\n\r\nAppropriate \u2013 It is important to confirm the validity and intent of the prescriber if forgery is suspected.\r\n\r\nC) Scrutinise the signature carefully, possibly checking against a known genuine prescription from the same prescriber\r\n\r\nAppropriate \u2013 Comparing the signature with a known example can help spot inconsistencies or signs of forgery.\r\n\r\nE) Use contact details for the prescriber that are obtained from a source other than the suspicious prescription\r\n\r\nAppropriate \u2013 Reinforces the need to avoid using the potentially forged document itself as a source of contact details.\r\n\r\nInvestigating Forged Prescriptions (MEP Guidance):\r\n\r\nAccording to the Medicines, Ethics and Practice (MEP) guide:\r\n\r\n- Pharmacists must be vigilant and take reasonable steps to verify the authenticity of prescriptions when there is any suspicion.\r\n\r\n- Use independent contact details to speak directly with the prescriber.\r\n\r\n- Do not rely solely on the title, signature, or contact details printed on the prescription if forgery is suspected.\r\n\r\n- It is acceptable to refuse to dispense if there is reasonable doubt about authenticity and to report suspicious activity to appropriate authorities (e.g. NHS counter fraud or local controlled drug liaison officer, if relevant).\r\n\r\n- Controlled drugs carry additional forgery risks and should be scrutinised even more closely.\r\n\r\nFor more information, please watch MEP lesson Chapter 2 (Professional And Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
