    "title": "**Which of the following would be inappropriate advice to provide?**",
    "text": "The GP from the surgery next door calls you as he wishes to complete a requisition form for some morphine ampoules. He tells you that he will be making several house visits for different terminally ill patients and wants to ensure their pain is managed appropriately.",
    "why": "A. The doctor cannot requisition for schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUnder the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines and the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001, it is entirely legal for a doctor to requisition Schedule 2 and Schedule 3 controlled drugs (CDs) such as morphine. Morphine is commonly used for pain management in palliative care, and a requisition can be made if all legal requirements are fulfilled. Suggesting otherwise is incorrect and inappropriate.\r\n\r\nRequirements for a Controlled Drug Requisition:\r\n\r\nA controlled drug requisition must include the following:\r\n\r\nSignature of the requester.\r\nName, address, and profession/occupation of the person requisitioning the drug.\r\nTotal quantity of the drug to be supplied.\r\nPurpose for which the drug is required (this can be inferred if the drug is being used within the normal course of professional practice).\r\nStandardised requisition form (FP10CDF) for CDs in England.\r\n\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nB. The doctor must sign the requisition himself as he is the recipient.\r\nThis is correct advice. The doctor requisitioning the CDs must sign the requisition form themselves, as per legal requirements.\r\n\r\nC. The doctor must state his profession/occupation on the requisition.\r\nThis is correct advice. The doctor must state their profession, as this is a legal requirement for all CD requisitions.\r\n\r\nD. The doctor must use a standardised NHS form when requesting the medication.\r\nThis is correct advice. In England, a standardised form (FP10CDF) must be used for requisitions of Schedule 2 and 3 CDs.\r\n\r\nE. The proposed use of the medicine must be stated on the requisition.\r\nWhile the explicit use does not have to be detailed in all cases, stating the purpose is considered good practice. For controlled drugs, the intended use is often implied (e.g., for professional medical use). This option is still correct advice when ensuring clarity on a requisition.\r\n\r\nA doctor can legally requisition Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs like morphine for legitimate medical purposes, provided all legal requirements are met. Controlled drug requisitions must be completed on a standardised form (FP10CDF in England), include the necessary details, and be signed by the requester. Misleading or incorrect advice about the requisition process could delay patient care and is inappropriate.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
    "resource_image": null,
