    "id": 2602,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is a contraindication for the patient?**",
    "text": "A 23 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy requesting to purchase Pyrocalm 20mg tablets for the treatment of dyspepsia. She informs you she is HIV positive and takes nelfinavir.\r\n\r\nThe SmPC for pyrocalm 20mg tablets has been provided for you\r\n[SmPC for Pyrocalm 20mg](https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/product/9154/smpc#gref)",
    "why": "She regularly takes nelfinavir.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Summary of Product Characteristics (SmPC) for Pyrocalm 20 mg tablets, which contain omeprazole, there is a significant drug interaction with nelfinavir, an antiretroviral medication used in the management of HIV. Proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), such as omeprazole, significantly reduce the plasma levels of nelfinavir, potentially reducing its therapeutic efficacy. Therefore, omeprazole and nelfinavir should not be used together, making the patient\u2019s regular use of nelfinavir a clear contraindication for the use of Pyrocalm.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nSymptoms lasting longer than 1 week is a common trigger for further medical evaluation, but it is not an absolute contraindication for PPIs.\r\nHypomagnesaemia and vitamin B12 deficiency are potential risks with long-term PPI use but not immediate contraindications.\r\nPrevious gastric ulcer is a condition often treated with PPIs, so it would not preclude their use.\r\nTherefore, the most significant contraindication in this case is the patient's regular use of nelfinavir, as outlined in the SmPC and supported by NICE recommendations.\r\n\r\nDyspepsia refers to a group of symptoms that typically include upper abdominal pain or discomfort, bloating, and indigestion. Initial management focuses on lifestyle changes such as weight reduction, reducing intake of alcohol, caffeine, and spicy foods, as well as stopping smoking. Pharmacological treatments for dyspepsia include antacids and proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) like omeprazole, which help reduce stomach acid and provide symptom relief. However, NICE emphasizes careful consideration of drug interactions, especially in patients on complex medication regimens, such as those taking nelfinavir for HIV. In such cases, PPIs like omeprazole should be avoided, and alternative therapies should be sought. Regular review and patient follow-up are recommended to ensure effective symptom control and to mitigate any risks related to long-term use of medications for dyspepsia.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
