    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "A 31 year old male patient presents to the pharmacy with a frontal aching headache. He explains to you his headache worsens at work as he spends a lot of time on computers. There is no photophobia or phonophobia.",
    "why": "The most appropriate action in this case is:\r\n\r\nRefer patient to optician for routine eye check.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\nThe patient's headache seems to be related to prolonged screen use, which may indicate eye strain or an issue with vision.\r\nThe absence of photophobia, phonophobia, or other alarming symptoms suggests that this is not a migraine or severe condition requiring urgent treatment or medication like Sumatriptan.\r\nCo-codamol could provide symptomatic relief, but it's not a long-term solution and might not address the underlying cause, which could be visual.\r\nProchlorperazine is used for nausea and vertigo, which are not indicated here.\r\n\r\n1. Initial Assessment:\r\nHistory Taking: The healthcare professional should gather a thorough history of the headache, including its duration, frequency, triggers, and associated symptoms. In this case, the patient mentions that the headache worsens while working on a computer and does not report photophobia (sensitivity to light) or phonophobia (sensitivity to sound).\r\nExclusion of Serious Conditions: The absence of severe symptoms, such as nausea, vomiting, or neurological deficits, suggests that this is likely a non-serious headache. This is consistent with tension-type headaches or headaches related to eye strain.\r\n2. Potential Causes:\r\nEye Strain: Spending long hours on a computer can lead to digital eye strain (also known as computer vision syndrome), which manifests as headaches, blurred vision, and discomfort. This may be particularly relevant in the patient's case, given the worsening of symptoms during work hours.\r\nTension-Type Headaches: These are the most common type of headache and are often triggered by stress, poor posture, and prolonged screen time, resulting in muscle tension in the neck and scalp.\r\n3. Management Recommendations:\r\nRefer for Routine Eye Check: Since the headache is aggravated by computer use, the most appropriate action is to refer the patient to an optician for a routine eye examination. This will help rule out vision problems that could be contributing to the headache, such as uncorrected refractive errors (e.g., myopia, hyperopia) or dry eyes.\r\nPain Relief: While selling analgesics like Co-codamol could provide symptomatic relief, it's not the best first-line approach here. NICE guidelines recommend addressing the underlying issue rather than just masking symptoms.\r\nAdvice on Ergonomics: The healthcare professional can also suggest ergonomic adjustments (like proper screen height, appropriate lighting, and regular breaks) to help alleviate symptoms related to prolonged screen use.\r\n4. Follow-Up:\r\nIf the headache persists after the eye check or if new symptoms develop, further assessment may be warranted to explore other potential causes or treatment options.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on Chapter 4 Neurology (headache and migraines)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
    "correct_answer_number": 1,
    "weighting": 3,
