    "title": "**What is the most appropriate action to take?**",
    "text": "A 23-year old female comes to the pharmacy with a prescription from their dentist. She informs you she has an abscess.\u00a0\r\nThe prescription has been presented below\u00a0\r\n![mepRxs](https://i.ibb.co/zGZVKy1/mepRxs.png)\r\n\r\nThe Dental Practitioners Formulary has been provided for this question\u00a0\r\n[Dental Practitioners Formulary](https://bnf.nice.org.uk/dental-practitioners-formulary/)",
    "why": "(C) Dispense amoxicillin and advise the patient to return to their dentist for a new prescription.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nDentists using an FP10D (NHS dental prescription form) are restricted to prescribing medications listed in the Dental Practitioners\u2019 Formulary (DPF). In this case, amoxicillin is appropriate and listed in the DPF for treating dental infections like abscesses. However, co-codamol is not listed in the DPF, and therefore cannot be dispensed under an NHS dental prescription. The correct action is to dispense the amoxicillin and advise the patient to return to their dentist for an alternative pain management prescription that complies with the DPF.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) Dispense both medications without any further action:\r\nIncorrect. Since co-codamol is not in the DPF, it should not be dispensed on an NHS prescription from a dentist. This would be against NHS prescription guidelines.\r\n\r\n(B) Dispense amoxicillin only:\r\nPartially correct, but without advising the patient to consult the dentist for alternative pain management, this action would leave the patient without necessary guidance on addressing her pain appropriately.\r\n\r\n(D) Dispense an alternative medication that is listed in the DPF:\r\nIncorrect. Substituting medications without authorization from the prescriber is not permitted. The patient should consult the dentist for a new prescription instead.\r\n\r\n(E) Refuse to dispense both medications:\r\nIncorrect. Amoxicillin is listed in the DPF, and withholding it would delay necessary treatment for the abscess.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe DPF limits the medications that NHS dentists can prescribe. For prescriptions issued on FP10D forms, only drugs listed in the DPF should be dispensed. In this scenario, dispensing amoxicillin complies with the guidelines, while co-codamol does not. Patients requiring non-DPF medications for pain relief should be advised to return to their dentist for an alternative DPF-compatible prescription or consider obtaining a private prescription if appropriate. This approach aligns with MEP guidance on the handling of restricted NHS dental prescriptions.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson Chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
