    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**What is the most appropriate action to take?**",
    "text": "A patient presents to your community with a prescription. They explain to you they are visiting their family. You do not have a contract with the Ministry of Defence.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\n\r\n![mepRxs-3](https://i.ibb.co/KqdjTpv/mepRxs-3.png)",
    "why": "(D) Treat it as a private prescription and ask the patient to pay full costs before receiving the medicine.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe FMed296 form is a prescription issued by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) for military personnel. If presented at a non-contracted pharmacy, like in this case, the prescription should be treated as a private one. The patient is responsible for paying the full costs upfront, and they can later seek reimbursement from their military unit if eligible.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) Advise the patient to return to their military base for a new prescription:\r\nNot required. The patient does not need a new prescription. They simply need to cover the costs themselves at a non-contracted pharmacy.\r\n\r\n(B) Dispense the medication without any further action:\r\nIncorrect. As the pharmacy is not contracted with the MOD, payment is required upfront, and the MOD will not cover direct costs in this situation.\r\n\r\n(C) Refuse to dispense the medication:\r\nUnnecessary. The prescription can be dispensed; however, it must be treated as a private prescription with upfront payment.\r\n\r\n(E) Send an invoice for services directly to the Ministry of Defence (MOD):\r\nIncorrect. Non-contracted pharmacies are not authorised to invoice the MOD directly. The patient must pay and handle reimbursement independently if eligible.\r\n\r\nIn the UK, prescriptions issued under FMed296 for MOD personnel are typically managed by contracted pharmacies. If a patient presents this prescription at a non-contracted pharmacy, it is treated as a private prescription, meaning the individual must pay the full cost of the medication upfront. This setup ensures that military personnel can still access necessary medicines, while maintaining clarity on payment responsibilities. The individual may pursue reimbursement directly through their military unit, contingent on their entitlements. This approach aligns with MEP guidance on handling MOD prescriptions outside contracted pharmacies.\r\n\r\nPlease for more information watch the MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
