    "id": 2491,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following actions would be the most appropriate to take?**",
    "text": "A French patient comes in with a prescription for morphine sulphate 10mg/5ml oral solution 10mL to be given every 4 hours. She explains to you that she is travelling and didn\u2019t want to carry lots of bottles around so a registered EU doctor wrote these prescriptions. Your counter assistant translated the prescription fully for you and you are confident of the appropriateness. The prescription is dated within the past 28 days.",
    "why": "E. You are satisfied with the prescription and supply the morphine sulphate oral solution.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, European Economic Area (EEA) professionals (such as doctors from France) are permitted to prescribe controlled drugs (CDs) within the UK, provided they comply with the necessary legal requirements outlined in the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 (Regulation 218).\r\n\r\nMorphine sulphate oral solution is a Schedule 5 controlled drug. Prescriptions for controlled drugs can be written by registered EEA doctors, as long as the prescription meets all the requirements, such as the correct prescription format, patient details, drug details, and appropriate dosage. A translation service like Language Line is an option if there are issues with understanding a non-English prescription, but since the prescription has already been translated by a reliable source (the counter assistant), this step is not necessary in this case.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the prescription is valid, and the most appropriate action is to supply the morphine sulphate oral solution.\r\n\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nA. Refuse the supply as CD prescriptions must be written by a UK doctor.\r\nThis is incorrect because EEA doctors are allowed to prescribe controlled drugs in the UK, as per Regulation 218 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012. There is no requirement for the prescription to be written by a UK doctor.\r\n\r\nB. Refuse the supply and request the patient make an appointment with a UK doctor to get a private prescription.\r\nThis is incorrect because the prescription from the EEA doctor is valid. There is no need to request a new prescription from a UK doctor, as long as all the prescription requirements have been met.\r\n\r\nC. Refuse the supply as you must not supply a prescription if it's not written in English.\r\nThis is incorrect. While it is important for prescriptions to be clear and understandable, a prescription written in a foreign language can be valid as long as it is properly translated. In this case, the translation has already been provided, so this is not a valid reason to refuse supply.\r\n\r\nD. Refuse the supply but supply another over-the-counter opiate such as co-codamol.\r\nThis is incorrect because supplying a different opiate (such as co-codamol) without proper medical authorisation would be inappropriate. The patient has a valid prescription for morphine sulphate, so it should be supplied as prescribed, not substituted with another medication.\r\n\r\nSummary:\r\n\r\nIn the UK, EEA doctors are authorised to prescribe controlled drugs such as morphine sulphate (a Schedule 5 controlled drug). The prescription must meet all legal requirements, including the correct format and details. If the prescription is in a foreign language, it can be valid as long as it is properly translated. Therefore, the prescription from the French doctor is legitimate, and the morphine sulphate oral solution should be supplied as prescribed.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
