    "title": "Mrs H, a regular patient of yours, brings her 11-year-old child in to your pharmacy. She tells you that they have recently returned from a safari trip in Africa. Her son has come up in an itch with small bumps rash where the mosquitoes have bitten him. You note that the bites are across his legs and upon inspection find that the skin is intact and not infected.",
    "text": "**Theme: Dermatological preparations**\r\n\r\n\r\n**For each of the following scenarios select the best option for over-the-counter treatment. Each option may be used once, more than once or not at all.**",
    "why": "(g) Hydrocortisone 1% cream\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nHydrocortisone 1% cream is the most suitable choice for this child\u2019s symptoms. It is a mild corticosteroid that effectively reduces inflammation and itching caused by mosquito bites, making it ideal for situations where the skin is intact and non-infected. This cream is appropriate for children over 10 and provides targeted relief for itchy, inflamed areas. Hydrocortisone offers a quicker and more effective response than other over-the-counter options, which are often less effective for multiple bites.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(a) Aloe vera gel: Aloe vera has a soothing, cooling effect that can help alleviate mild skin irritation. However, it lacks the anti-inflammatory properties needed to fully relieve the persistent itching from multiple insect bites.\r\n\r\n(b) Aqueous calamine cream: Calamine is commonly used to relieve minor itchiness but does not match hydrocortisone\u2019s effectiveness for reducing inflammation and discomfort in cases of extensive bites.\r\n\r\n(c) Aveeno\u00ae lotion: While Aveeno provides moisturising benefits, it lacks anti-inflammatory effects, making it less suitable for relieving itching and inflammation from insect bites.\r\n\r\n(d) Dermol\u00ae wash: Dermol acts as an antimicrobial and emollient, which can help prevent skin infections but is not formulated to target itching relief from bites.\r\n\r\n(e) Diprobase\u00ae cream: Primarily a moisturiser, Diprobase is more suitable for dry skin conditions rather than addressing itching or inflammation from bites.\r\n\r\n(f) Eumovate\u00ae cream: Eumovate, a moderate-potency corticosteroid, is stronger than hydrocortisone and typically avoided for children without a professional recommendation.\r\n\r\n(h) Oilatum\u00ae Junior Bath Additive: This bath additive is beneficial for managing general dry or irritated skin but is not designed to alleviate the specific itching and inflammation caused by insect bites.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, managing insect bites, particularly in children, involves a combination of symptomatic relief, prevention of infection, and monitoring for any worsening of symptoms. For uncomplicated bites where the skin is intact and free from infection, a mild corticosteroid like hydrocortisone 1% cream is recommended to reduce localised itching and inflammation. This is generally safe for short-term use in children over 10 and provides effective relief from the discomfort caused by multiple bites, especially on exposed areas like the legs.\r\n\r\nIn cases where bites cause only mild irritation, cooling products such as aloe vera gel or aqueous calamine cream may be used for soothing. Emollient creams or lotions like Aveeno or Diprobase are helpful for dry skin but may not provide targeted relief for itching from bites. For young children or those with sensitive skin, it\u2019s essential to choose low-potency treatments and avoid stronger corticosteroids like Eumovate without a healthcare provider's recommendation.\r\n\r\nIf there are any signs of infection, such as redness, warmth, or pus at the bite sites, an antiseptic wash or consultation with a healthcare professional may be advised. Additional precautions, such as regular emollient use and avoiding scratching, can also help prevent worsening symptoms and skin breakdown.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
