    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a legal requirement on prescriptions?**",
    "text": "Regulation 217 of the human medicines regulations states the legal requirements for prescriptions",
    "why": "a) Date of birth\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nUnder Regulation 217 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, the date of birth is not a legal requirement on prescriptions. While the date of birth may be included in practice, especially to avoid confusion with similarly named patients, it is not a mandatory field under the regulations. However, if the patient is under 12 years of age, the age of the patient must be included on the prescription.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\nb) Date of prescription\r\n\r\nThe date of prescription is a legal requirement. It must be included on the prescription to determine the validity period and ensure that the prescription is within the allowed timeframe for dispensing.\r\n\r\nc) Particulars of prescriber\r\n\r\nThe particulars of the prescriber (such as their name, address, and professional qualification) are legally required. This ensures that the prescription is legitimate and traceable to the prescriber.\r\n\r\nd) Patient name and address\r\n\r\nThe patient's name and address are legally required to identify the recipient of the prescribed medication. This is essential for the correct dispensation of the medication.\r\n\r\ne) Signature by appropriate practitioner\r\n\r\nExplanation: The signature of the appropriate practitioner (the prescriber) is a legal requirement to verify the authenticity of the prescription.\r\nSummary on Legal Requirements for Prescriptions\r\nRegulation 217 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 sets out clear legal requirements for prescriptions to ensure safety and proper dispensing. These include the date of prescription, details of the prescriber, patient's name and address, and the signature of the appropriate practitioner.\r\nWhile the date of birth is not mandatory, the age of a patient under 12 years is a legal requirement. Ensuring that these elements are present helps maintain legal compliance, traceability, and patient safety.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
