    "id": 2566,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most likely causative organism of her condition?**",
    "text": "A 25-year-old woman presents to your pharmacy with a sore throat, fever, and malaise. She says she has been feeling unwell for the past three days and has difficulty swallowing. You examine her throat and see the white spots at the back of throat and swollen glands.",
    "why": "Streptococcus pyogenes\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe most likely causative organism in this case is Streptococcus pyogenes, which is responsible for bacterial pharyngitis, commonly known as strep throat. The symptoms presented\u2014sore throat, fever, malaise, difficulty swallowing, swollen glands, and white spots at the back of the throat\u2014are all typical of a streptococcal infection. S. pyogenes infections can lead to pharyngitis, which is characterised by white patches on the tonsils, significant discomfort, and swollen lymph nodes, especially in the absence of other viral symptoms such as cough or runny nose.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nCandida albicans: This yeast causes oral thrush, which may present as white patches in the mouth or throat, especially in immunocompromised individuals or those on antibiotics. However, it is generally not accompanied by fever or swollen glands.\r\n\r\nEpstein-Barr virus: Although Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) can cause symptoms like a sore throat, fever, and swollen glands, it typically leads to infectious mononucleosis, which presents more gradually and often includes extreme fatigue. Swollen glands in EBV tend to be more generalised, and while white spots can be present, EBV is less likely to cause acute, localised throat pain as seen in strep throat.\r\n\r\nFusobacterium necrophorum: This bacterium is linked to Lemierre\u2019s syndrome, a rare complication following a sore throat that typically presents with high fever and neck swelling due to thrombophlebitis. It is less likely to be a primary cause of throat infection in this age group.\r\n\r\nHerpes simplex virus: Herpes simplex infections can cause a sore throat, fever, and swollen glands, but they are more often associated with painful ulcers or blisters rather than white patches and are typically localized to the lips or oral cavity.\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A Streptococcus) is a common cause of bacterial pharyngitis, particularly in children and young adults. Strep throat is characterised by sudden onset of sore throat, fever, tender and swollen lymph nodes, and white or yellow exudate on the tonsils. NICE recommends antibiotic treatment in cases where bacterial infection is confirmed or highly suspected, especially when symptoms are severe or persistent. First-line treatment typically includes penicillin or amoxicillin, but alternative antibiotics are available for those with allergies. Symptomatic care with hydration, rest, and analgesics is also recommended to relieve throat pain and fever.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 2 (Respiratory):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
