    "id": 2587,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following conditions is the most likely diagnosis?**",
    "text": "A 28-year-old patient visits your community pharmacy complaining of an itchy and scaly rash on their elbows and knees. Upon examination, you notice well-defined, silvery plaques with underlying erythema. The patient reports that their nails also appear pitted and discoloured.",
    "why": "Psoriasis\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nThe most likely diagnosis is psoriasis, based on the presence of characteristic silvery plaques with underlying redness (erythema) on areas such as the elbows and knees. Nail involvement, including pitting and discolouration, is also a common sign of psoriasis.\r\n\r\nAtopic Dermatitis (Eczema) typically presents with dry, cracked, inflamed skin but is more common on flexural areas (inside the elbows, behind the knees) and doesn't usually feature silvery plaques.\r\nContact Dermatitis results from exposure to irritants or allergens and generally causes redness, itching, and blistering, rather than well-defined plaques with silvery scales.\r\nRosacea affects the face, causing redness, flushing, and visible blood vessels, and would not present with plaques or nail changes.\r\nUrticaria (Hives) typically presents as raised, itchy welts rather than scaly plaques.\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, psoriasis is a chronic inflammatory skin condition that features well-demarcated, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales, often found on the scalp, elbows, knees, and lower back. Nail involvement, such as pitting or discolouration, is also a common feature. Psoriasis can range in severity and may be associated with psoriatic arthritis in some patients.\r\n\r\nTreatment for psoriasis, as recommended by NICE, begins with topical therapies, including emollients to soothe the skin and prevent dryness, and topical corticosteroids or vitamin D analogues to reduce inflammation and plaque formation. For moderate-to-severe psoriasis, phototherapy or systemic treatments, such as methotrexate or biologic agents, may be necessary. Regular follow-up and referral to a dermatologist are advised for long-term management, particularly in more severe cases or when topical treatments are insufficient.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
