    "id": 2565,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most appropriate advice to give him?**",
    "text": "A 60-year-old man visits your community pharmacy with a sore throat that has been bothering him for the past 3 weeks. He says he has been taking paracetamol 500mg four times a day, but it has not helped much. He also has a history of type 2 diabetes and takes metformin 1g twice daily. He has no fever, cough, or difficulty swallowing. He does not smoke or drink alcohol.",
    "why": "C) Refer him to his GP for further assessment.\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nGiven the patient's persistent sore throat lasting over three weeks despite regular use of paracetamol, referral to his GP is warranted for further assessment. This is particularly important due to his age and medical history of type 2 diabetes, as it may complicate his condition or affect his immune response. Chronic throat symptoms can indicate an underlying issue that may require further investigation.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Lozenges containing benzocaine may provide temporary relief but will not address the underlying cause of the persistent sore throat.\r\nB) Gargling with salt water can be soothing but is unlikely to resolve ongoing symptoms and does not substitute for medical evaluation.\r\nD) Switching to ibuprofen may provide symptomatic relief, but again, it does not address the underlying issue and could mask symptoms that need evaluation.\r\nE) Continuing with paracetamol without seeking further advice is not appropriate given the duration of symptoms.\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, the management of sore throat symptoms requires careful consideration, especially in older adults or those with pre-existing medical conditions. A sore throat that persists for more than three weeks warrants further investigation to rule out potential serious underlying conditions such as chronic infections, gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), or even malignancies. The guidelines emphasize the importance of assessing additional symptoms and risk factors, which can influence the decision to refer to a GP. In this patient's case, the combination of persistent symptoms and his history of diabetes increases the likelihood of complications, making a referral essential. Proper evaluation will enable targeted treatment and ensure any serious conditions are identified and managed appropriately, safeguarding the patient\u2019s health and well-being.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 2 (Respiratory):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
