    "title": "**What is the most suitable cough syrup to recommend in this scenario?**",
    "text": "A 35-year-old female with type 1 diabetes comes to your community pharmacy with a complaint of dry cough for the past week. She says she has no fever, chest pain, or weight loss. She has good glycaemic control and takes insulin glargine and insulin aspart. She does not smoke and works as a nurse. She asks you for a cough syrup to soothe her throat.",
    "why": "B) A cough syrup containing dextromethorphan\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nDextromethorphan is an antitussive agent that effectively suppresses a dry cough by acting on the central nervous system. This makes it suitable for short-term relief in a patient with diabetes, as it has no known effects on blood glucose levels when taken as directed. Unlike syrups containing sugar or alcohol, dextromethorphan-based products avoid the risk of blood glucose fluctuations, making them safer for individuals with diabetes. Additionally, dextromethorphan does not interact with insulin, aligning with the patient\u2019s regimen of insulin glargine and insulin aspart for good glycaemic control.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) A cough syrup containing codeine: Codeine is an opioid antitussive that can effectively relieve cough, but it may cause drowsiness and has the potential for dependence, which makes it less suitable for a patient like this, who is seeking simple throat soothing.\r\nC) A cough syrup containing guaifenesin: Guaifenesin is an expectorant used to thin mucus, more suitable for productive coughs, whereas this patient\u2019s symptoms suggest a dry cough.\r\nD) A cough syrup containing sugar: Sugar-containing syrups should generally be avoided in diabetic patients, as they can cause blood glucose levels to spike.\r\nE) A cough syrup containing alcohol: Alcohol in cough syrups can dry out the throat and may interfere with blood glucose stability, which is especially unsuitable for someone managing type 1 diabetes.\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, diabetic patients with a dry cough should avoid syrups with added sugars or alcohol, as these can cause fluctuations in blood glucose levels. Dextromethorphan, as a non-sedative antitussive without these additives, is recommended for dry cough relief in patients with diabetes. If a cough persists beyond three weeks, a further evaluation is advisable to rule out any underlying conditions.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 2 (Respiratory):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
