    "title": "**What is the most appropriate action to take?**",
    "text": "A 45-year-old female presents to your community pharmacy with a dry cough that has lasted a month. She says she has no fever, chest pain, or shortness of breath. She has a history of asthma and takes salbutamol inhaler as needed. She smokes 10 cigarettes per day and works as a receptionist in a busy office. She asks you for an over-the-counter cough suppressant to relieve her symptoms.",
    "why": "a) Advise her to see her GP as soon as possible\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor a 45-year-old woman with a persistent dry cough lasting more than three weeks, the best course of action is to advise her to see her GP as soon as possible. Chronic cough, especially in a smoker, can be indicative of underlying conditions such as asthma complications, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), or even early signs of lung disease. Although she is currently asymptomatic regarding chest pain or shortness of breath, her smoking habit and occupation in a busy office could exacerbate respiratory issues and may contribute to the persistence of her cough. Referral to a GP allows for further investigation, which may include spirometry, imaging, or adjustments to her asthma management.\r\n\r\nOver-the-counter (OTC) cough suppressants, like those containing codeine or dextromethorphan, may temporarily relieve symptoms but do not address the underlying cause. Frequent use of her salbutamol inhaler or increasing fluid intake could alleviate irritation but is not a substitute for medical evaluation, given the chronicity of her symptoms and her smoking history.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nb) Advise her to use her salbutamol inhaler more frequently: While this could relieve symptoms, it does not address the underlying cause of the persistent cough.\r\nc) Advise her to stop smoking and increase her fluid intake: Smoking cessation and hydration can improve respiratory health; however, due to the chronic nature of her cough, a GP assessment remains essential.\r\nd) Recommend a cough suppressant containing codeine: Codeine is an opioid-based cough suppressant and is not recommended due to potential dependency, especially in chronic cough cases.\r\ne) Recommend a cough suppressant containing dextromethorphan: Although dextromethorphan is suitable for dry cough, it does not address potential underlying causes that could require intervention.\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines recommend that patients with a persistent cough lasting more than three weeks, particularly if they smoke or have a history of respiratory conditions, should be evaluated by a GP. For smokers, chronic cough may be an early indicator of COPD or other respiratory issues. Referral is crucial to ensure accurate diagnosis and management, which may include smoking cessation support and adjustments to asthma therapy. Additionally, patient education on avoiding irritants, monitoring symptoms, and understanding asthma control can improve long-term respiratory health.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 2 (Respiratory):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
