    "title": "**How many days left can the patient collect the prescription before it expires?**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription for a 26-year-old female of childbearing potential who has been prescribed isotretinoin for severe acne. The patient has dropped in the prescription to you and informed you she will collect it later. Today\u2019s date is the 11th December 2023\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\n![3](https://i.ibb.co/Mk8NsY0/3.png \"400x600\")",
    "why": "(b) 4 days\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPrescriptions for isotretinoin for women of childbearing potential, under the Pregnancy Prevention Programme (PPP), are valid for only 7 days from the date on the prescription due to the risk of teratogenicity. This strict 7-day timeframe aims to minimise the risk of pregnancy during treatment, as isotretinoin has a high risk of causing severe birth defects.\r\n\r\nIn this case:\r\n\r\nThe prescription date is 8th December.\r\nThe current date is 11th December.\r\nCounting from the date the prescription was written:\r\n\r\n8th, 9th, and 10th December have already passed.\r\nThe patient has 4 days remaining (11th, 12th, 13th, and 14th December) to collect the medication before the prescription expires.\r\nThus, the last day to dispense this prescription is 14th December.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor isotretinoin under PPP:\r\n\r\nPrescriptions are valid for 7 days from the date written.\r\nThe patient has 4 days left to collect the prescription before it becomes invalid.\r\n\r\nWatch MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
