    "why": "Correct answer: \r\n\r\nA) Dispense the item and keep a record for 3 years\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Veterinary Medicines Regulations (VMR) and RPS/MEP guidance, when a community pharmacist dispenses a veterinary prescription (e.g. POM-V or POM-VPS), the record of supply must be retained for 5 years, not 3.\r\n\r\nKeeping a record for only 3 years is insufficient and would be non-compliant with UK law \u2014 making it the least appropriate action in the list.\r\n\r\nExplanation of other options:\r\n\r\nB) Dispense and keep a record for 5 years \r\n\r\nThis meets the legal requirement under VMR 2013 (still current), which applies to both vets and pharmacists.\r\n\r\nC) Ensure the words \u201cunder the cascade\u201d are on the prescription \r\n\r\nOnly required when supplying a human medicine for an animal where no suitable veterinary product exists.\r\n\r\nD) Label must include the species of the animal\r\n\r\nHelps ensure appropriate use and traceability.\r\n\r\nE) Label must include the words \u201cfor animal treatment only\u201d \r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
