    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 66 year old male patient presents to the pharmacy requesting advice for this tongue. He informs you he was prescribed co-amoxiclav 500mg/125mg tablets for the treatment of a dental infection. He has no allergies and takes warfarin 3mg for the prevention of embolic stroke in atrial fibrillaton.\u00a0\r\nA photograph of the mans symptoms is below:\u00a0![oral-thrush](https://i.ibb.co/s5RTb5D/oral-thrush.jpg \"750x600\")",
    "why": "The most appropriate advice for the patient is:\r\n\r\nHe is experiencing a side effect of co-amoxiclav and whilst safe to continue taking it, he should see his GP for nystatin to be prescribed.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe patient\u2019s symptoms are consistent with oral thrush (candidiasis), a known side effect of antibiotic use, including co-amoxiclav. Antibiotics can disrupt the normal balance of bacteria and fungi in the mouth, leading to overgrowth of Candida species. This is particularly important in a patient who takes warfarin, as Daktarin (miconazole) oral gel can interact with warfarin and increase the risk of bleeding. Therefore, the safest and most effective treatment option is nystatin, which is recommended by NICE guidelines for managing oral thrush in patients on warfarin since it has fewer interactions.\r\n\r\nAdvising the patient to continue taking co-amoxiclav while seeking a prescription for nystatin is appropriate as stopping the antibiotic may interrupt treatment for the dental infection.\r\nDaktarin (miconazole) oral gel interacts with warfarin and should be avoided due to the increased risk of bleeding complications.\r\nStopping co-amoxiclav is unnecessary unless the patient develops severe allergic reactions or other significant adverse effects.\r\nThe symptoms are indeed a known side effect of co-amoxiclav, making the last option incorrect.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance on Management of Oral Thrush\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, the management of oral thrush in patients taking antibiotics or on anticoagulation therapy like warfarin includes:\r\n\r\nAntifungal Treatment: Nystatin suspension is often the preferred treatment for oral thrush in patients taking warfarin, as it has minimal systemic absorption and is less likely to interact with anticoagulant therapy.\r\n\r\nMaintaining Good Oral Hygiene: Patients should be advised to rinse their mouths after taking the antibiotic and maintain oral hygiene to reduce fungal growth.\r\n\r\nDietary Advice: Avoid sugary foods and beverages that may promote fungal growth, and encourage regular drinking of water to help cleanse the mouth.\r\n\r\nMonitoring INR Levels: Given the patient\u2019s use of warfarin, it is crucial that INR levels are monitored closely if any medication changes occur, including the addition of nystatin.\r\n\r\nAdditional Insights\r\n\r\nOral thrush is a common complication of antibiotic therapy, particularly broad-spectrum antibiotics like co-amoxiclav. Patients taking anticoagulants, such as warfarin, are at an increased risk of interactions with certain antifungal agents like miconazole, which can inhibit the metabolism of warfarin, raising INR levels and increasing the risk of bleeding.\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines emphasise the importance of selecting antifungal treatments with minimal interaction risks in such patients. Nystatin is effective and poses less risk, making it the preferred choice. If symptoms persist despite appropriate treatment, or if the patient experiences significant side effects from the antibiotic, further evaluation by a healthcare provider may be necessary. Regular communication between the patient, pharmacist, and GP can help ensure safe and effective management of both the dental infection and oral thrush.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lessons: \r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
