    "text": "A 63 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy requesting advice for her eye. Her vision is blurred, with halo vision and is experiencing severe headaches.\u00a0\r\nShe informs you she has recently been in hospital with an asthma attack. She shows you her discharge letter which contains the following information.\u00a0\r\n\r\n*Reason for Admission and Presenting Complaint(s):* Life threatening acute asthma,\u00a0\r\nRelevant Investigations and Results:\r\n*PEFR < 33%*\r\n*Sp02: 89%*\r\n*(PaCO2): 5.9*\r\n*Heart rate: 112 bpm*\r\n*Procedures and Treatment:* nebulized salbutamol 5mg and nebulized ipratropium bromide 500 micrograms\r\n*Discharged medicines:* Salbutamol 100mcg/dose inhaler, beclometasone 100mcg/dose inhaler\r\n\r\nA picture of her eye has been provided below:\r\n![glaucoma](https://i.ibb.co/7vhmmH7/glaucoma.jpg \"750x500\")",
    "why": "Nebulised ipatropium has been known to cause acute glaucoma. The patients symptoms are classic symptoms of acute glaucoma.\r\n\r\n### Glaucoma \r\n\r\n**Definition**: \r\n- Glaucoma is a group of eye diseases causing progressive optic neuropathy, often associated with raised intraocular pressure (IOP).\r\n\r\n**Types**:\r\n1. **Primary Open-Angle Glaucoma (POAG)**:\r\n   - Most common type.\r\n   - Affects about 2% of people in the UK over 40 years.\r\n   - Usually insidious onset and chronic.\r\n   - Typically affects both eyes.\r\n   - Associated with raised IOP but can occur with normal IOP.\r\n\r\n2. **Primary Angle Closure Glaucoma (PACG)**:\r\n   - Affects about 0.4% of people in the UK over 40 years.\r\n   - Often asymptomatic chronic PACG.\r\n   - Acute angle closure is a medical emergency.\r\n\r\n**Risk Factors for Acute Angle Closure**:\r\n- Female, Asian, long-sighted, or older age.\r\n- Symptoms: painful red eye, blurred vision, headaches, nausea, halos around lights, semi-dilated pupil, tender eye.\r\n\r\n**Management**:\r\n- **Acute Angle Closure**:\r\n  - Immediate admission for ophthalmology assessment.\r\n  - If admission is delayed, start emergency treatment:\r\n    - Lie flat with face up.\r\n    - Administer pilocarpine drops (2% for blue eyes, 4% for brown eyes).\r\n    - Oral acetazolamide (500 mg) if no contraindications.\r\n    - Provide analgesia and anti-emetics as needed.\r\n\r\n- **Chronic Glaucoma**:\r\n  - Refer to optometrist or ophthalmologist.\r\n  - Treatment aims to reduce IOP to prevent vision loss.\r\n  - First-line treatment for IOP of 24mmHg or more, PACG, or at risk of visual impairment: 360\u00b0 selective laser trabeculoplasty.\r\n\r\n**Complications**:\r\n- Untreated glaucoma can lead to irreversible vision loss.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the BNF lesson on  Chapter 11 (Eyes):\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
