    "title": "A 17-year-old female patient who presents with an itchy, red rash on her elbows and knees, which has been present for several weeks. She has a family history of atopic eczema and has already tried using E45 cream which improved the condition slightly, but it is still there and \u2018starting to bother\u2019 her.",
    "text": "**Theme: Dermatological preparations**\r\n\r\n**For each of the following scenarios select the best option for over-the-counter treatment. Each option may be used once, more than once or not at all.**",
    "why": "g) Hydrocortisone 1% cream\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nHydrocortisone 1% cream is a mild corticosteroid and is appropriate for treating mild to moderate eczema flares in individuals over 10 years old, making it suitable for this 17-year-old. It is effective in reducing itching and inflammation on areas like the elbows and knees where the skin is intact but irritated. Since E45 cream provided only partial relief, hydrocortisone 1% is a reasonable next step for short-term use to help clear up the lingering rash.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\na) Aloe vera gel: While it offers a soothing effect, aloe vera is generally inadequate for treating eczema-related inflammation.\r\nb) Aqueous calamine cream: Calamine can relieve mild itching but doesn\u2019t address eczema\u2019s underlying inflammation, making it less effective than hydrocortisone.\r\nc) Aveeno\u00ae lotion: Aveeno is an emollient that helps hydrate the skin but lacks the anti-inflammatory properties needed for treating an eczema flare.\r\nd) Dermol\u00ae wash: This is an antimicrobial and emollient wash that can be helpful for skin hydration and infection prevention, but it\u2019s not effective for reducing active inflammation.\r\ne) Diprobase\u00ae cream: While Diprobase is an effective emollient for daily use, it doesn\u2019t contain active ingredients to reduce inflammation.\r\nf) Eumovate\u00ae cream: Eumovate contains clobetasone butyrate, a moderate-potency corticosteroid. It is generally reserved for more severe or persistent cases that haven\u2019t responded to milder options. Pharmacists typically recommend hydrocortisone 1% before progressing to a higher-potency steroid.\r\nh) Oilatum\u00ae Junior Bath Additive: Oilatum is a bath emollient beneficial for hydration but is not intended to reduce localized inflammation from eczema.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, emollients are the foundation of eczema management to maintain skin hydration and support the barrier function. For mild flares, hydrocortisone 1% is suitable and effective, especially in individuals over the age of 10. Moderate potency corticosteroids, such as Eumovate, are recommended only if symptoms persist and milder corticosteroids prove ineffective. Eczema management also includes avoiding known triggers, using emollients regularly, and monitoring for signs of infection, such as redness, oozing, or increased pain. Regular follow-up and adjustments to treatment can help keep eczema under control and prevent future flares.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
