    "id": 2494,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which one of the following best describes a mandatory activity that must be completed by pharmacy contractors on an annual basis as part of this?**",
    "text": "Clinical governance is defined as a systematic approach to maintaining and improving the quality of patient care within a health system.",
    "why": "A. Clinical audit\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nClinical governance is a fundamental framework in healthcare systems, encompassing various activities to ensure high standards of care. Community pharmacies must adhere to these standards through mandatory requirements such as clinical audits and other governance-related activities.\r\n\r\nA. Clinical audit (Correct):\r\n\r\nPharmacy contractors must conduct at least two clinical audits annually:\r\n\r\nOne nationally determined clinical audit, such as one defined by NHS England.\r\nOne locally chosen clinical audit, tailored to meet specific service needs.\r\nThese audits evaluate clinical practices and outcomes, identifying areas for improvement to enhance patient care.\r\n\r\nB. Clinical governance toolkit (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nWhile the toolkit is a resource that supports the implementation of clinical governance practices, completing it is not a mandatory annual requirement.\r\n\r\nC. Reaccreditation of services (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nReaccreditation may be required for specific advanced services but is not universally mandatory on an annual basis as part of clinical governance.\r\n\r\nD. Registering of premises (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nRegistering pharmacy premises is a legal requirement but is not a recurring annual activity tied to clinical governance.\r\n\r\nE. Unpublished patient survey (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nPharmacies must conduct an annual patient satisfaction survey, but its results must be published, making the phrase \"unpublished patient survey\" inaccurate.\r\n\r\nAs part of clinical governance, pharmacy contractors are required to complete two clinical audits annually\u2014one nationally mandated and one locally determined. These audits serve to review and improve clinical practices, ensuring high-quality patient care and compliance with healthcare standards.\r\n\r\nOther activities such as publishing patient survey results, maintaining up-to-date governance practices, and reaccreditation of services complement clinical governance but are not universally mandated annually. By adhering to these requirements, pharmacies uphold their commitment to safe, effective, and patient-centred care.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
