    "id": 2611,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the LEAST appropriate self advice for onychomycosis?**",
    "text": "A 23 year old male patient presents to the pharmacy with onychomycosis on his left big toe.\u00a0\r\nHe has purchased amorolfine 5% nail lacquer and would like some self care advice.",
    "why": "The LEAST appropriate self-care advice for a patient with onychomycosis is:\r\n\r\nWear well-fitting occlusive shoes.\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, it's important to avoid wearing occlusive shoes when managing fungal infections such as onychomycosis, as they can trap moisture and heat, providing a favorable environment for fungal growth. Instead, footwear should be non-occlusive, allowing air circulation to keep the feet cool and dry. The other self-care options listed are appropriate and align with NICE recommendations for managing fungal infections.\r\n\r\nAvoid trauma to the nails if possible: Protecting nails from injury is crucial as trauma can worsen the infection or allow fungi to penetrate the nail further.\r\nKeep his toenails short and filed down: This practice reduces the fungal load and aids the effectiveness of topical treatments like amorolfine.\r\nMaintain good foot hygiene: Washing and thoroughly drying feet, especially between the toes, helps reduce moisture and fungal growth.\r\nWear cotton absorbent socks: These socks help absorb moisture and keep the feet dry, creating an unfavorable environment for fungal organisms.\r\nSelf-Care Advice for Athlete's Foot According to NICE Guidelines\r\nWhile managing onychomycosis, NICE guidelines also provide comprehensive self-care advice for athlete's foot, another common fungal infection:\r\n\r\nWear well-fitting, non-occlusive footwear: This helps keep the feet cool and dry, reducing moisture accumulation.\r\nConsider replacing old footwear: Old shoes may harbor fungal spores, so replacing them helps prevent reinfection.\r\nMaintain good foot hygiene: Wearing different shoes every 2\u20133 days allows each pair to dry fully, minimizing the risk of fungal growth.\r\nWear cotton, absorbent socks: These socks keep the feet dry and comfortable by absorbing excess moisture.\r\nAvoid scratching the affected skin: Scratching can spread the infection to other body parts or individuals.\r\nDry feet thoroughly after washing, especially between the toes, to reduce moisture retention.\r\nDo not share towels and wash them frequently to minimize the spread of the infection.\r\nWear protective footwear in communal areas like showers, locker rooms, and gyms to lower the risk of acquiring or transmitting fungal infections.\r\nChildren with athlete's foot do not need to be excluded from school or nursery.\r\n\r\nBoth onychomycosis and athlete\u2019s foot are commonly caused by similar fungal organisms, and preventing these infections relies heavily on maintaining good foot hygiene and choosing appropriate footwear. While antifungal treatments play a crucial role, effective prevention strategies are equally important in managing these infections and reducing recurrence. By following these NICE-recommended self-care tips, patients can significantly enhance the efficacy of treatments and promote overall foot health.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson on Chapter 8 Dermatology:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
    "correct_answer_number": 5,
    "weighting": 3,
