    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action to take?**",
    "text": "Mrs K comes into your pharmacy on Saturday morning. She explains that she is visiting her daughter from out of town and has forgotten her medicine. She tells you that she is currently taking phenobarbital tablets at a dose of 80mg each night for epilepsy. She says that she usually receives the Actavis brand and shows you an empty box which is dated within the past month and is clearly labelled with the dose instructions.",
    "why": "B. Explain that you can make a supply which is limited to only 5 days\u2019 worth of treatment.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUnder the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, an emergency supply of a controlled drug is permitted in specific circumstances. For Schedule 3 controlled drugs, such as phenobarbital (when prescribed for epilepsy), the pharmacist can supply no more than 5 days\u2019 worth of treatment.\r\n\r\nThis supply is permissible because:\r\n\r\nPhenobarbital is the only Schedule 3 CD permitted for emergency supply under these conditions, provided the pharmacist is satisfied of its necessity.\r\nThe patient must provide evidence of prior use (e.g., a labelled box or verbal confirmation).\r\nThe pharmacist must make a record of the supply, including the patient\u2019s GP details, the medicine details, and the rationale for the emergency supply.\r\n\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nA. Explain that you can make a supply if she furnishes a prescription within 72 hours.\r\nThis is incorrect because phenobarbital does not require the patient to furnish a prescription within 72 hours for an emergency supply. This requirement applies to some other CDs under specific conditions.\r\n\r\nC. Explain that you cannot make a supply as controlled drugs fall outside of emergency supply rules.\r\nThis is incorrect because phenobarbital, when used for epilepsy, is specifically allowed under emergency supply rules despite being a Schedule 3 controlled drug.\r\n\r\nD. Supply the drug for a 30-day duration and make a record detailing this alongside her doctor\u2019s details.\r\nThis is incorrect because only a 5-day supply is permitted for Schedule 3 controlled drugs under emergency supply rules. A 30-day supply applies only to certain prescription-only medicines, not controlled drugs.\r\n\r\nE. Supply the drug and make a record detailing her general practitioner\u2019s name and registration number.\r\nThis is incorrect because while a record must be made, the supply is limited to 5 days for phenobarbital, not an unrestricted amount. Additionally, there is no requirement to record the GP's registration number.\r\n\r\n\r\nEmergency supply regulations allow pharmacists to provide a maximum of 5 days' worth of Schedule 3 controlled drugs, such as phenobarbital, for epilepsy. This exception ensures that patients can access essential medications for a chronic condition when unexpected circumstances arise. Pharmacists must exercise professional judgment, ensure the supply is appropriate, and document all necessary details, including the patient\u2019s GP information and rationale for the supply.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
