    "text": "A 22 year old male patient presents to the pharmacy with a painful eyelid. He informs you there has been no changes in vision. He has had the symptoms for the past 3 days.\r\nA picture of the eyelid has been provided below:\r\n\r\n\r\n![stye](https://i.ibb.co/mqk6XHM/stye.jpg \"600x600\")",
    "why": "The patient has a stye which is self limiting. The patient can use a warm compress to release the pus in the stye.\r\n\r\nA **stye** (hordeolum) is an acute infection or inflammation of the eyelid margin, usually caused by a staphylococcal infection. There are two types:\r\n\r\n- **External Stye**: Located on the eyelid margin, often from an infected eyelash follicle or associated gland.\r\n- **Internal Stye**: Found on the conjunctival surface of the eyelid, caused by an infection of a Meibomian gland.\r\n\r\n**Risk Factors**: Chronic blepharitis, acne rosacea.\r\n\r\n**Symptoms**: Painful, localized swelling (papule or furuncle) near the eyelid margin, typically unilateral but can be bilateral. Symptoms usually resolve within 5\u20137 days once the stye drains or ruptures.\r\n\r\n**Complications**: May include infective conjunctivitis, Meibomian cyst formation, or rarely, periorbital or orbital cellulitis.\r\n\r\n**Assessment**:\r\n- Determine the timescale of symptoms, previous episodes, and associated risk factors.\r\n- Examine for typical features, check for complications, and rule out atypical diagnoses (e.g., malignant eyelid tumour).\r\n\r\n**Management**:\r\n- Reassure patients that styes are usually self-limiting and serious complications are rare.\r\n- For severe cases with periorbital or orbital cellulitis, arrange emergency hospital admission.\r\n- Urgent referral to an ophthalmologist if a malignant tumour is suspected.\r\n- Advise self-care measures: apply warm compresses, avoid eye makeup and contact lenses until healed.\r\n- Manage underlying conditions (blepharitis, acne rosacea) to reduce recurrence.\r\n- Prescribe topical antibiotics only if there are signs of infective conjunctivitis.\r\n\r\n**For Painful External Styes**:\r\n- Consider plucking the affected eyelash to facilitate drainage.\r\n- Incision and drainage may be performed by a trained healthcare professional if appropriate.\r\n\r\n**Referral to Ophthalmologist**:\r\n- If the stye does not improve with primary care management.\r\n- If an internal stye is particularly large and painful.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 3 Opthalmology and Otology:\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
