    "text": "A 17 year old male presents to the pharmacy. He informs you he has suffered with eczema since childhood. He informs you he has a flare up of his eczema and lesions inside the elbows are weeping and have a yellow crust.",
    "why": "Advise to see his GP as soon as possible for treatment\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe presence of weeping lesions with a yellow crust suggests a possible secondary bacterial infection, commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus in individuals with eczema. When eczema becomes infected, immediate medical attention is required, as a GP can prescribe appropriate treatment such as oral antibiotics or stronger topical corticosteroids. The patient should avoid using over-the-counter hydrocortisone or other topical treatments without medical advice as these may worsen the infection.\r\n\r\nThe other options are less appropriate because:\r\n\r\nOintments are more moisturising than creams, but they should not be used on weeping or infected skin as they can trap moisture and bacteria, worsening the infection.\r\nHydrocortisone 1% cream is not suitable for use on infected eczema without medical advice, as it could exacerbate the infection.\r\nChlorophenamine (an antihistamine) may help reduce itching, but it does not address the underlying infection, which is the primary concern in this case.\r\nUsing a lotion on broken skin is not recommended as lotions are more watery and can irritate broken or weeping skin, potentially leading to further discomfort and infection.\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines recommend that patients with infected eczema should be referred to a healthcare provider for appropriate treatment. Signs of infection include weeping lesions, yellow crusts, or an unusual smell. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and appropriate topical corticosteroids to manage inflammation and infection. Infected eczema should not be self-treated with over-the-counter emollients, corticosteroids, or antihistamines without consulting a healthcare professional. Managing infection early can prevent complications and further skin damage.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
