    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most likely diagnosis?**",
    "text": "A 45-year-old woman presents to your pharmacy with a complaint of multiple small ulcers in her mouth. She says she has been having them for the past 5 days, and they are very painful and interfere with her eating and speaking. She has tried various over-the-counter products, such as bonjela, orabase, and corsodyl mouthwash, but none of them have helped. She also says she has no other medical conditions or allergies, and she does not smoke or drink alcohol. She asks you for your advice on what else she can do to treat her mouth ulcers.\r\n\r\nYou examine her mouth and see multiple pin point ulcers at the front of the mouth and at the sides of the tongue.",
    "why": "The most likely diagnosis for the patient is:\r\n\r\nHerpetiform ulcers\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nHerpetiform ulcers are characterised by multiple small ulcers with irregular edges and a red border, typically occurring in clusters. Unlike cold sores, which are caused by the herpes simplex virus, herpetiform ulcers are associated with an immune-mediated process and are often recurrent. These ulcers can last for several weeks and may also be a cutaneous manifestation of coeliac disease, a gluten-sensitive enteropathy.\r\n\r\nThe other options are less likely to be the cause of the patient's symptoms due to differing clinical features:\r\n\r\nCanker sores (aphthous ulcers) usually appear as larger, single ulcers or in small groups and typically heal within two weeks.\r\nCold sores are caused by herpes simplex virus and generally present as blisters on the lips or around the mouth.\r\nOral lichen planus is a chronic inflammatory condition that presents with white lace-like patches, red areas, or ulcers on the oral mucosa.\r\nOral cancer typically presents as a single, persistent, painless ulcer with indurated edges, which is not consistent with the current presentation.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance on Management of Herpetiform Ulcers\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines and supported by the book Community Pharmacy by Rutter, management strategies for herpetiform ulcers include:\r\n\r\nTopical Treatments: The use of a topical steroid mouthwash can help reduce inflammation and pain associated with the ulcers.\r\n\r\nOral Rinses: Antiseptic mouthwashes, such as chlorhexidine, may help maintain oral hygiene and reduce the risk of secondary infection.\r\n\r\nPain Relief: Over-the-counter analgesics (e.g., paracetamol or ibuprofen) can assist in managing discomfort.\r\n\r\nAvoidance of Irritants: Patients should avoid spicy, acidic, or abrasive foods to minimise irritation and pain during the healing process.\r\n\r\nHydration and Nutrition: Encourage the intake of soft foods and adequate hydration to support healing, especially as eating can be painful.\r\n\r\nAdditional Insights\r\n\r\nHerpetiform ulcers can arise from various triggers, including stress, hormonal changes, or certain food intolerances, and are particularly noted as a cutaneous manifestation of coeliac disease. They typically recur and can be more severe than standard canker sores.\r\n\r\nPatients should be advised to review their symptoms after two weeks of treatment; if there is no improvement or if there are signs of infection, malignancy, or systemic disease, a referral to a GP or dentist is warranted for further evaluation.\r\n\r\nEducating the patient on good oral hygiene practices and the importance of managing stress can be beneficial in preventing future outbreaks. This comprehensive approach ensures that patients receive not only symptomatic relief but also guidance on maintaining their overall oral health and addressing any underlying conditions effectively.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson on Chapter 8 Dermatology:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
