    "text": "A controlled drugs register must be maintained in the pharmacy to record the receipt and supply of schedule 2 controlled drugs.",
    "why": "D) Registers must be retained for 2 years after the first entry\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nAccording to the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001, the legal requirement is to retain controlled drugs registers for 2 years after the last entry made, not the first. This ensures that the records are available for inspection or audit and that any controlled drugs transactions are fully traceable.\r\n\r\nExplanation of other options:\r\n\r\nA) Copies of registers must be shown to an inspector upon request: This is correct. Pharmacists must make their controlled drugs registers available to authorised persons (such as inspectors) for inspection as per the regulations. This ensures accountability and compliance with the law.\r\n\r\nB) Records can be kept in their original form: This is correct. Controlled drugs registers can be kept either in paper form or electronically, as long as they are accurate and easily accessible.\r\n\r\nC) Registers must be kept at the premises: This is correct. Controlled drugs registers must be kept on-site at the pharmacy where the controlled drugs are stored. This is necessary for regular access and auditing.\r\n\r\nE) Registers must be retained for 2 years after the last entry: This is correct. The legal retention period is two years from the last entry in the register, allowing sufficient time for auditing and inspection.\r\n\r\n\r\nPharmacies are required to maintain a register of all Schedule 2 controlled drugs (CDs), documenting their receipt, supply, and any other movement. This register must be kept at the pharmacy premises and available for inspection by authorities. The records must be retained for two years from the last entry, which ensures the traceability and accountability of controlled drug transactions. Electronic and paper records are both acceptable, provided they are accurate and accessible. This is in line with the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 (as amended), which set out the requirements for the handling of controlled substances to ensure their proper use and prevent misuse.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
