    "id": 2580,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's symptoms?**",
    "text": "A 59 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy with a rash. She explains she has had symptoms for the past few weeks and has not seen any improvement. Her rash is on her elbows, knees and scalp.\r\nA picture of the rash has been shown below:\u00a0\r\n![psoriasis](https://i.ibb.co/qJc5tP9/psoriasis.jpg \"650x500\")",
    "why": "d) Psoriasis\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPsoriasis is the most likely diagnosis based on the patient\u2019s symptoms and presentation. This chronic skin condition commonly presents with well-defined, scaly, red plaques on extensor surfaces like the elbows, knees, and scalp. The persistent nature of the symptoms and the specific areas affected align closely with plaque psoriasis, the most prevalent form of this condition.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Options\r\n\r\na) Atopic eczema\r\n\r\nWhile eczema can affect various areas of the body, it typically involves the flexural regions (e.g., inner elbows, behind the knees) and is associated with intense itching. Additionally, atopic eczema often presents with a history of allergies or asthma and is not typically localized to the extensor areas like psoriasis.\r\n\r\nb) Acne vulgaris\r\n\r\nAcne vulgaris is a skin condition that primarily affects the face, chest, and back, presenting with blackheads, whiteheads, and sometimes pustules. It does not manifest as red, scaly plaques on the elbows, knees, or scalp, making it an unlikely cause in this case.\r\n\r\nc) Pityriasis versicolor\r\n\r\nPityriasis versicolor is a fungal skin infection that causes small, flaky patches, often lighter or darker than surrounding skin. It generally affects the trunk, shoulders, and back, not areas like the elbows and knees, making it less likely in this scenario.\r\n\r\ne) Rosacea\r\n\r\nRosacea is typically confined to the face, presenting with persistent redness, visible blood vessels, and occasionally pustules. It does not affect the scalp, elbows, or knees, ruling it out as a probable cause for this patient\u2019s symptoms.\r\n\r\n\r\nPsoriasis is a chronic, immune-mediated skin condition characterised by recurrent flares of red, scaly plaques, most commonly on the elbows, knees, and scalp. According to NICE guidelines, the initial management of psoriasis focuses on topical treatments to control symptoms and reduce inflammation. Emollients are often used to maintain skin hydration, and topical corticosteroids and vitamin D analogues are recommended to reduce scaling and soothe inflammation.\r\n\r\nFor patients with more extensive or severe psoriasis, NICE advises considering phototherapy or systemic treatments, such as methotrexate or biologics, to control symptoms. Lifestyle factors, including managing stress, smoking cessation, and avoiding potential triggers (e.g., infections, skin trauma) are emphasised to help prevent flare-ups. NICE also highlights the importance of patient education on the chronic nature of psoriasis, setting realistic expectations, and ensuring adherence to treatment to improve overall quality of life. Regular follow-ups to monitor response to therapy are also advised for optimal management.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
    "correct_answer_number": 4,
    "weighting": 3,
    "answers": [
      {
        "text": "Atopic eczema",
        "answer_number": 1
      },
      {
        "text": "Acne vulgaris",
        "answer_number": 2
      },
      {
        "text": "Pityriasis versicolor",
        "answer_number": 3
      },
      {
        "text": "Psoriasis",
        "answer_number": 4
      },
      {
        "text": "Rosacea",
        "answer_number": 5
      }
    ],
    "is_free": false
