    "text": "It is a Saturday morning in your local community pharmacy. You receive a prescription for a 31 year old female patient from Greece. She explains to you she is in the UK working for 6 months so her doctor has postdated a number of prescriptions for her\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription is below:\u00a0\r\n![Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-11-08-28](https://i.ibb.co/YfJtxVM/Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-11-08-28.png)\r\n\r\nAn extract of the BNF has been provided for you.\u00a0\r\n[Tretinoin BNF extract](https://bnf.nice.org.uk/drugs/tretinoin-specialist-drug/medicinal-forms/)",
    "why": "(C) Refer the patient to NHS 111 for a prescription with a UK license.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe prescription provided meets the legal requirements set out under Regulation 218 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 for overseas prescriptions. However, Retin-A 0.1% cream is not available in the UK under this brand name or as a direct equivalent. Therefore, it cannot be dispensed as prescribed. The best course of action is to refer the patient to NHS 111, where they can receive guidance on how to obtain a UK-licensed equivalent of tretinoin cream. This ensures the patient can access the treatment they need while following UK legal and regulatory guidelines.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) Advise the patient to return to their doctor and request a new prescription of Retin-A:\r\nIncorrect. This would be impractical, as the patient\u2019s doctor is based in Greece, and Retin-A is unlikely to be prescribed with a UK license there. NHS 111 is a more suitable option for obtaining UK-licensed medication.\r\n\r\n(B) Provide an emergency supply of Retin-A 0.1% cream and request a new prescription from their doctor in Greece:\r\nIncorrect. Retin-A is not available in the UK market, and an emergency supply can only be given if the medicine is obtainable in the UK. An emergency supply would not be appropriate in this case.\r\n\r\n(D) Refuse to dispense the prescription because it does not meet legal requirements:\r\nIncorrect. The prescription is legally valid, but the medication is unavailable in the UK. Referring the patient to NHS 111 for a UK-licensed equivalent is a more suitable response.\r\n\r\n(E) The prescription meets all legal requirements therefore dispense the prescription:\r\nIncorrect. While the prescription is legally valid, Retin-A is unavailable in the UK. Dispensing it as prescribed is not possible.\r\n\r\nOverseas prescriptions are permissible if they meet specific legal requirements, such as including the prescriber's qualifications, address, and clear instructions. However, overseas medications not marketed in the UK cannot be dispensed under these prescriptions. In such cases, referring patients to NHS 111 for a licensed UK equivalent is the recommended course of action, as per MEP guidelines, ensuring patient safety and compliance with UK medicine regulations.\r\n\r\nPlease for more information watch the MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
