    "id": 2492,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Regarding this mechanism of supply, which of the following is correct?**",
    "text": "Salbutamol inhalers can be supplied to schools without a prescription for administration in an emergency by trained persons using a signed order.",
    "why": "B. A signed order must be signed by the head teacher.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThe mechanism for supplying salbutamol inhalers to schools without a prescription is regulated under legislation to ensure these devices are available for emergencies, such as severe asthma attacks in pupils.\r\n\r\nA. Appropriately headed paper is legally required (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nHeaded paper is not a legal requirement, though it is a professional recommendation to help validate the authenticity of the signed order.\r\n\r\nB. A signed order must be signed by the head teacher (Correct):\r\n\r\nLegally, the signed order must be authorised and signed by a person with management responsibility, typically the head teacher or principal of the school. This ensures accountability and proper oversight of the supply process.\r\n\r\nC. A spacer device should be provided with each supply of an inhaler (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nWhile spacer devices can improve the effectiveness of salbutamol delivery, there is no legal requirement to supply a spacer with each inhaler under this mechanism. Schools are responsible for ensuring they have the appropriate devices for use.\r\n\r\nD. The signed order must be retained for 5 years from the date of supply, and a POM register entry made only (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nIt is true that the signed order must be retained for 2 years (not 5 years) and that an entry must be made in the Prescription-Only Medicine (POM) register. This ensures accurate record-keeping and accountability.\r\n\r\nE. Ventolin\u00ae branded inhalers are approved for supply via this mechanism (Incorrect):\r\n\r\nBoth branded (e.g., Ventolin\u00ae) and generic salbutamol inhalers are approved for supply under this mechanism. There is no restriction to specific brands.\r\n\r\nSchools can obtain salbutamol inhalers without a prescription to be used in emergencies for pupils diagnosed with asthma or prescribed an inhaler. The supply must follow specific legal requirements, including:\r\n\r\nA signed order authorised by the head teacher or principal.\r\nRetention of the signed order for 2 years, with an appropriate entry in the POM register.\r\nThe supply can include either generic or branded inhalers, but a spacer device is not mandatory.\r\nWhile appropriately headed paper is not a legal requirement, its use is encouraged to maintain professional standards and ensure clarity. This policy ensures rapid access to lifesaving treatment in emergencies while maintaining robust record-keeping and oversight.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
