    "text": "Regulation 218 of the Human Medicines Regulations states the legal requirements for EEA or Switzerland prescriptions",
    "why": "a) Medicines which are not MHRA approved in the UK are acceptable\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThis statement is incorrect because medicines prescribed on EEA/Swiss prescriptions must be approved by the UK\u2019s Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA). Medicines that are not MHRA-approved cannot be legally dispensed in the UK, even if prescribed by a valid EEA/Swiss prescriber.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\nb) Only Schedule 4 and 5 Controlled Drugs can be prescribed\r\n\r\nThis is correct. EEA and Swiss prescribers can legally prescribe only Schedule 4 and 5 Controlled Drugs. They are not allowed to prescribe Controlled Drugs from Schedules 1, 2, or 3.\r\n\r\nc) Patients' full first name, surname, and date of birth are needed\r\n\r\nThis is correct. The prescription must include the patient's full name and date of birth to ensure accurate identification and to meet legal requirements.\r\n\r\nd) Prescriptions are valid for 6 months unless the medicine is a Schedule 4 Controlled Drug\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Prescriptions issued by EEA or Swiss prescribers are valid for 6 months unless they involve Schedule 4 Controlled Drugs, in which case they are valid for 28 days from the date of issue.\r\n\r\ne) Prescribers' direct contact details, including email address and telephone number\r\n\r\nThis is correct. The prescription must include the prescriber's direct contact details (such as email address and telephone number) to allow the dispensing pharmacist to verify the prescription if needed. This ensures authenticity and compliance with the legal framework.\r\n\r\nRegulation 218 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 outlines the requirements for accepting prescriptions issued by EEA or Swiss healthcare professionals. Key points include:\r\n\r\nMedicine Approval: Only medicines approved by the UK\u2019s MHRA can be dispensed.\r\nControlled Drugs: Only Schedule 4 and 5 Controlled Drugs can be prescribed by EEA/Swiss prescribers.\r\nValidity: Prescriptions are generally valid for 6 months, except for Schedule 4 Controlled Drugs, which are valid for 28 days.\r\nPatient and Prescriber Details: Prescriptions must include the patient\u2019s full name and date of birth as well as the prescriber's name, qualifications, contact details, and work address.\r\nPharmacists must carefully assess the validity and compliance of EEA/Swiss prescriptions before dispensing, ensuring patient safety and adherence to UK law.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
