    "title": "**Which of the following is the most likely cause of the man\u2019s symptoms?**",
    "text": "A 79-year-old male patient presents to the pharmacy. He explains his eyes often has a burning sensation and often his vision is blurred which improves when blinking. He has heart failure and takes the following medication\r\n\r\nBumetanide 1mg tablets\u00a0\r\nRamipril 10mg tablets\u00a0\r\nBisoprolol 5mg tablets\u00a0\r\nSpironolactone 25mg tablets",
    "why": "Burning sensation, blurred vision that improves with blinking, and advanced age are common symptoms of dry eye syndrome.\r\nMedications such as diuretics (Bumetanide), ACE inhibitors (Ramipril), beta-blockers (Bisoprolol), and potassium-sparing diuretics (Spironolactone) can contribute to dry eye symptoms as a side effect.\r\nDry eye is a common condition, especially in the elderly, and it can be exacerbated by medications that affect tear production or composition.\r\n\r\n- Dry eye disease (keratoconjunctivitis sicca) is a chronic condition involving loss of tear film homeostasis, leading to reduced tear production or instability, with discomfort and visual symptoms.\r\n  \r\n- **Two main types:**\r\n  - **Evaporative dry eye** (more common) \u2014 caused by increased tear evaporation due to a deficient lipid layer.\r\n  - **Aqueous deficient dry eye** \u2014 due to reduced tear secretion from the lacrimal glands.\r\n\r\n- **Causes include:**\r\n  - Meibomian gland dysfunction, blepharitis, age-related changes, Sj\u00f6gren\u2019s syndrome, rosacea, reduced blinking, environmental factors, and iatrogenic causes (contact lens use, medications, or post-surgery).\r\n\r\n- **Complications:**\r\n  - Impacts daily activities, causes anxiety and depression, and may lead to corneal damage or severe visual loss (rare).\r\n\r\n- **Symptoms:**\r\n  - Eye irritation, dryness, transient blurring, watery eyes, mild redness, or mucous discharge.\r\n\r\n- **Assessment:**\r\n  - Symptom history, impact on quality of life, possible causes, ocular history, medication, visual acuity, and examination for lid issues or inflammation.\r\n\r\n- **Management:**\r\n  - Provide information and support, suggest lifestyle adjustments (warm compresses, lid hygiene), reduce contributing drug use, manage any related conditions, recommend tear substitutes, and arrange follow-up if needed.\r\n\r\n- **Referral to specialist:**\r\n  - For red flag symptoms, suspected serious underlying cause, uncertain diagnosis, systemic conditions (e.g. Sj\u00f6gren\u2019s), abnormal lid anatomy, or unresponsive symptoms after 4\u201312 weeks.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 3 Opthalmology and Otology (Dry Eye):\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
