    "title": "**What is the most likely causative organism of the infant's condition?**",
    "text": "A 6-month-old infant is brought to the pharmacy by their mother. The infant has a history of eczema and has not received the first two doses of the 6-in-1 vaccine. The mother says that the infant has had a runny nose and a mild cough for the past two weeks, and recently developed episodes of severe coughing followed by a whooping sound and vomiting. The infant is feeding poorly and has a temperature of 38.2\u00b0C. On examination, you notice that the infant has a red face and watery eyes during the coughing fits. The infant is not drooling or having difficulty breathing.",
    "why": "The infant has classic symptoms of whooping cough (pertussis), which is a  highly infectious bacterial infection caused by bacterium Bordetella pertussis\u00b9. Whooping cough has three phases of symptoms:\r\n\r\nCatarrhal phase (1\u20132 weeks): Resembles a common cold with symptoms like runny nose, malaise, and mild cough. Fever is rare.\r\n\r\nParoxysmal phase (around 1 week): Characterised by intense coughing fits followed by a 'whoop' sound (less common in adults and infants) or vomiting. Infants may experience apnea.\r\n\r\nConvalescent phase (2\u20133 weeks): Gradual improvement, though coughing may recur with future infections.\r\n\r\nVaccination or prior infection can result in milder symptoms but does not offer lifelong protection. Infants under six months are at higher risk of severe illness and death.\r\n\r\nWhooping cough is suspected if a person has had a cough for 14 days or more, with symptoms like paroxysmal cough, inspiratory 'whoop', vomiting after coughing, or unexplained apnea in infants, especially if they had contact with a confirmed case.\r\n\r\nManagement includes:\r\n\r\nAdmitting severe cases, particularly infants.\r\nAntibiotics within 14 days of cough onset (or 21 days for close contacts).\r\nSymptomatic relief and managing close contacts.\r\nEnsuring vaccinations are up to date.\r\nExclusion from nursery, school, or work is advised until 48 hours of antibiotic treatment or 14\u201321 days without treatment, depending on the case.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 1 Paediatrics (Whooping Cough):\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
