    "title": "**Which of the following would be the most appropriate course of action?**",
    "text": "A 32-year-old woman presents to your pharmacy with which she describes as 'a burning, acidic sensation' after eating. Upon consultation, you discover the woman also feels sick and is burping a lot. She is eating and drinking normally, and does not have any other symptoms, but is 34 weeks pregnant.\u00a0\r\n\r\nShe does not smoke and has tried both diet and lifestyle modifications, as suggested by her midwife, for the last week, but the symptoms have persisted. She has not yet tried any medication, and does not take any other regular medication.",
    "why": "d) Advise her to take Gaviscon\u00ae liquid and see her GP if her symptoms do not improve\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor a pregnant woman at 34 weeks experiencing symptoms of acid reflux and heartburn, Gaviscon\u00ae liquid is a safe, effective, and first-line treatment option. Gaviscon contains alginates and antacids, which provide a soothing barrier on the stomach contents, reducing reflux symptoms without systemic absorption, making it safe during pregnancy. If her symptoms do not improve, a GP consultation is recommended for further assessment and potential prescription options.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\na) Advise her to eat smaller and more regular meals: Although smaller, frequent meals can help manage heartburn, she has already tried lifestyle and dietary modifications per her midwife's advice. Additional medication is now warranted to relieve her persistent symptoms.\r\nb) Advise her to purchase ranitidine tablets and see her GP if her symptoms do not improve: Ranitidine is not recommended as a first-line OTC treatment for pregnant women due to limited availability and safety concerns in pregnancy. Prescription antacids should only be considered if other measures are ineffective.\r\nc) Advise her to take Nexium\u00ae tablets and see her GP if her symptoms do not improve: Nexium\u00ae (esomeprazole) is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) and is typically reserved for use under medical supervision in pregnancy due to its systemic effects. It is not recommended as a first-line OTC treatment without GP guidance.\r\ne) Advise her to see her GP to confirm the diagnosis and prescribe an appropriate drug: While a GP visit may be needed if symptoms persist, an OTC option like Gaviscon is safe and suitable as a first-line option before consulting a GP.\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines suggest managing heartburn and acid reflux in pregnancy initially with dietary and lifestyle changes, such as smaller, frequent meals and avoiding triggers. For women who continue to experience symptoms despite these measures, antacids or alginate-containing products like Gaviscon are recommended as safe, non-systemic options to alleviate discomfort. If symptoms persist, a healthcare provider may evaluate the need for further treatment.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
