    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription for a 27-year-old male who has been prescribed fentanyl patches for pain relief after a road traffic accident.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\n\r\n![1](https://i.ibb.co/0C4XFdW/1.png \"400x600\")",
    "why": "(b) Amend the quantity of the prescription to meet all legal requirements and then dispense the prescription\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUnder the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001, Schedule 2 controlled drugs, like fentanyl, have strict prescription requirements, including having the quantity written in both words and figures. However, if either the words or figures are missing (but not both), pharmacists have the authority to make a technical amendment. This involves completing the missing part, signing, and including their full name and GPhC number to validate the correction.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) Advise the patient to return to their GP for a new prescription: This is not necessary unless both words and figures for the quantity are missing. A pharmacist can amend the prescription if only one part is absent.\r\n\r\n(c) Contact the GP surgery to specify which brand of fentanyl patch is needed: This step would only be required if the prescription specified a brand-related issue. In this case, no brand-related clarification is necessary.\r\n\r\n(d) Provide an emergency supply and request a new prescription from the GP: Emergency supply is not permitted for Schedule 2 controlled drugs like fentanyl, making this option inappropriate.\r\n\r\n(e) The prescription meets all legal requirements therefore dispense the prescription: This option assumes no amendments are needed, but if either the words or figures for the quantity are missing, it does not meet the requirements until corrected.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guide and NICE guidelines, prescriptions for Schedule 2 controlled drugs such as fentanyl must meet specific requirements. The prescription must include the total quantity written in both words and figures, ensuring clarity and preventing potential misuse or errors. If one part of the quantity (either words or figures) is missing, pharmacists can amend this detail, provided they add their signature, full name, and registration number.\r\n\r\nNote:\r\n\r\nEmergency supplies are strictly prohibited for Schedule 2 controlled substances (except phenobarbital for epilepsy), and dispensing without correct quantity information is unlawful. These guidelines ensure that prescriptions for controlled drugs meet rigorous standards for both patient safety and legal compliance.\r\n\r\nWatch MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
