    "text": "You are the responsible pharmacist and you teaching trainee pharmacists about Croup.",
    "why": "Croup is commonly caused by parainfluenza viruses, particularly types 1 and 2.\r\n\r\nCroup (laryngotracheobronchitis) is a common respiratory illness in children aged 6 months to 3 years, usually caused by viruses like parainfluenza types 1 or 3. It is characterised by a sudden onset of a seal-like barking cough, often with hoarseness, stridor, and breathing difficulties. Symptoms tend to worsen at night and with agitation. \r\n\r\nBefore the cough starts, non-specific upper respiratory symptoms like cough, runny nose, and fever may occur for 12 to 72 hours. The clinical features arise due to inflammation and swelling of the upper airways, causing narrowing of the subglottic region.\r\n\r\nCroup severity is classified as:\r\n- **Mild:** Barking cough without stridor or chest recession at rest.\r\n- **Moderate:** Barking cough with stridor and chest recession, but no agitation or lethargy.\r\n- **Severe:** Barking cough with stridor, chest recession, and agitation or lethargy.\r\n- **Impending respiratory failure:** Increasing airway obstruction, chest wall and abdominal movement issues, fatigue, pallor, cyanosis, and a drop in consciousness.\r\n\r\nMild cases can be managed at home and typically resolve within 48 hours, though some may last up to a week. Parents are advised to give paracetamol or ibuprofen for fever and pain, and seek urgent medical help if symptoms worsen. \r\n\r\nHospital admission is required for children with chronic lung or heart disease, immunodeficiency, fast breathing (over 60 breaths/minute), high fever, or poor fluid intake. Children with moderate or severe croup, or those at risk of respiratory failure, should also be hospitalised.\r\n\r\nAll children with croup should receive a single dose of oral dexamethasone (0.15 mg/kg). For those too unwell for oral treatment, nebulised budesonide or intramuscular dexamethasone are alternative options.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 1 Paediatrics (Croup and paedriatics quiz):\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
