    "id": 2518,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a criteria to enable emergency supplies at patient request?**",
    "text": "Regulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations enables emergency supplies at the request of a patient",
    "why": "E) Prescription must be obtained within 72 hours\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor an emergency supply at the request of a patient, there is no legal requirement that a prescription be obtained within 72 hours. This criterion applies only when an emergency supply is requested by a prescriber, not by the patient. At a patient\u2019s request, the pharmacist may provide an emergency supply if specific conditions are met, but there is no time limit for obtaining a subsequent prescription.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Maximum 5 days supply for Schedule 4 Controlled drugs \u2013 This is a correct requirement. For Schedule 4 Part I controlled drugs (such as Clobazam), an emergency supply at a patient\u2019s request can only cover a maximum of 5 days. This regulation helps control the availability of these drugs while addressing immediate patient needs in a limited capacity.\r\n\r\nB) Pharmacist is satisfied there is an immediate need \u2013 This criterion is essential for emergency supplies. The pharmacist must be convinced that the patient has an urgent requirement for the medication, making an immediate supply necessary to maintain their health or prevent adverse effects from an interrupted treatment.\r\n\r\nC) Pharmacist to interview the patient \u2013 A direct interview with the patient is required for an emergency supply at the patient\u2019s request. This interaction allows the pharmacist to assess the patient\u2019s condition, determine the necessity of the medication, and ensure safe dispensing based on the patient\u2019s history.\r\n\r\nD) POM requested must have been used as previous treatment \u2013 The medication requested for an emergency supply must be one that the patient has previously been prescribed, ensuring that the patient is familiar with the medication and its effects. This requirement also supports continuity in treatment, reducing the risk of adverse reactions to unfamiliar medications.\r\n\r\n\r\nRegulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 governs emergency supplies of prescription-only medicines (POMs) at a patient\u2019s request, enabling pharmacists to provide urgent medication under specific conditions. The key criteria for patient-requested emergency supplies include that the pharmacist is satisfied there is an immediate need, the medicine has been previously prescribed for the patient, and an interview is conducted to assess the situation. For Schedule 4 Part I controlled drugs, only a maximum of 5 days\u2019 supply can be issued, ensuring adherence to controlled substance regulations.\r\n\r\nUnlike emergency supplies requested by a prescriber, there is no statutory requirement for obtaining a prescription within a certain time frame when an emergency supply is at the patient\u2019s request. These guidelines are designed to balance access to essential medications with regulatory control, supporting pharmacists in making safe, compliant decisions when addressing urgent patient needs.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
