    "why": "E) Oxycodone injection\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPhysiotherapists who are independent prescribers are authorised to prescribe certain controlled medicines. However, there are restrictions on injectable forms of certain drugs. Oxycodone, for example, can only be prescribed by independent prescribers for oral formulations, not for injectable forms. Therefore, physiotherapists are unable to prescribe injectable oxycodone.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Dihydrocodeine tablets \u2013 Physiotherapists can prescribe this oral form of dihydrocodeine, a controlled medicine used for pain relief.\r\n\r\nB) Fentanyl patches \u2013 Fentanyl patches are a strong opioid prescribed for pain management, and physiotherapists can prescribe them in their patch form.\r\n\r\nC) Lorazepam tablets \u2013 Lorazepam, a benzodiazepine, can be prescribed by physiotherapists for managing anxiety or sleep disorders.\r\n\r\nD) Morphine injection \u2013 Physiotherapists can prescribe injectable morphine for pain management, making it an acceptable option for prescription.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Medicines, Ethics and Practice (MEP) guidelines specify that while physiotherapists can prescribe certain controlled drugs, they are restricted from prescribing injectable versions of certain medications, such as oxycodone. It is important to be aware of these prescribing limits to ensure compliance with regulations and patient safety.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
