    "title": "**Which of the following medicines CANNOT be prescribed by a dentist on a NHS prescription?**",
    "text": "You are teaching your trainee pharmacist about NHS dental prescriptions and their restrictions in prescribing.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the Dental Practitioners Formulary has been provided for you.\u00a0\r\n\r\nhttps://bnf.nice.org.uk/dental-practitioners-formulary/",
    "why": "b) Co-codamol tablets\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nCo-codamol tablets are not listed in the Dental Practitioners Formulary (DPF), which defines the medicines that dentists can legally prescribe on the NHS. If a medication is not included in the DPF, dentists are not authorised to prescribe it on an NHS prescription, although they may do so privately if appropriate.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Aciclovir cream\r\n\r\nThis is included in the DPF and can be prescribed by dentists for treating conditions like cold sores (herpes labialis) or oral herpetic infections.\r\n\r\nc) Dihydrocodeine tablets\r\n\r\nDihydrocodeine is listed in the DPF and can be prescribed by dentists for short-term pain management when NSAIDs or paracetamol are insufficient.\r\n\r\nd) Lidocaine spray\r\n\r\nLidocaine spray is part of the DPF and is commonly used for topical anaesthesia in dental procedures or to relieve oral discomfort.\r\n\r\ne) Temazepam tablets\r\n\r\nTemazepam tablets are listed in the DPF for use as a sedative in dental practice, particularly for anxious patients undergoing dental procedures.\r\n\r\nThe Dental Practitioners Formulary (DPF) is a section of the British National Formulary (BNF) that outlines the medicines dentists can prescribe on the NHS. Dentists are restricted to prescribing drugs listed in the DPF, which ensures prescribing remains relevant to dental practice. Key considerations:\r\n\r\nPrescriptions must align with the treatment of dental conditions.\r\nMedications outside the DPF cannot be prescribed on the NHS but may be issued privately.\r\nDentists can prescribe Schedule 2, 3, and 4 Controlled Drugs within the DPF, adhering to legal and clinical guidelines.\r\nPharmacists should verify that dental prescriptions comply with the DPF to ensure legality and appropriateness.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
