    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following would NOT require a referral?**",
    "text": "You are teaching your trainee Pharmacist regarding herpes simplex labialis",
    "why": "A 34-year-old pregnant female who requires aciclovir 5% cream for a cold sore\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nA 34-year-old pregnant female with a typical cold sore does not require a referral if she is only seeking to purchase aciclovir 5% cream, which is safe to use during pregnancy for topical treatment. Pregnancy is not a contraindication for topical aciclovir use in the case of herpes simplex labialis, and it can be managed in a pharmacy setting.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the other patients would require referral for the following reasons:\r\n\r\nA 65-year-old patient with a sore for 3 weeks: This indicates a chronic or non-healing sore, which may require investigation for underlying conditions, such as malignancy or a resistant infection.\r\nA 23-year-old patient with cold sores inside their mouth: Herpes simplex labialis typically affects the lips and surrounding areas. Sores inside the mouth are not common for typical cold sores and could indicate another condition, such as herpetic gingivostomatitis or an oral ulcer, which requires referral.\r\nAn 18-year-old patient with a cold sore that has spread to the face: This suggests a more extensive or complicated infection, potentially requiring antiviral medication beyond topical treatment or further medical assessment.\r\nA 48-year-old patient with severe and widespread lesions: Widespread or severe lesions may indicate a more serious form of herpes simplex infection or an immunocompromised state, and these patients should be referred for systemic treatment and further investigation.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, herpes simplex labialis (cold sores) usually presents as a recurrent, self-limiting viral infection that can be managed with topical antiviral agents, such as aciclovir 5% cream. Most cases resolve within 10\u201314 days, and treatment is aimed at reducing the duration and severity of symptoms. Referral is warranted for patients who have chronic, non-healing sores, widespread infections, involvement of the oral mucosa, or if they are immunocompromised. Safe use of topical antiviral treatments in pregnant women is well-established, making them suitable candidates for over-the-counter management unless the infection is severe or atypical.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
