    "text": "A 22 year old male presents to the pharmacy with abdominal discomfort and bouts of bloody diarrhoea where each bowel movement is urgent.",
    "why": "Ulcerative colitis\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe symptoms described\u2014abdominal discomfort, bloody diarrhoea, and urgent bowel movements\u2014are characteristic of ulcerative colitis, a chronic inflammatory bowel disease (IBD). Ulcerative colitis typically affects the colon and rectum, leading to inflammation, ulceration, and bleeding in the bowel. These symptoms align with a flare-up of this condition, which often presents in young adults.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nColorectal cancer: While colorectal cancer can cause changes in bowel habits and sometimes bleeding, it usually presents with more subtle, gradual symptoms, such as weight loss and non-specific abdominal discomfort. Bloody diarrhoea with urgency is more typical of an inflammatory condition like ulcerative colitis.\r\n\r\nIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS): IBS can cause abdominal discomfort and changes in bowel habits, but it is not typically associated with bloody diarrhoea or urgent bowel movements. The presence of blood suggests an inflammatory or structural issue, which is not common in IBS.\r\n\r\nGastro-enteritis: Gastro-enteritis usually presents with non-bloody diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting, and abdominal cramps. Bloody diarrhoea is more indicative of a more severe inflammatory or infectious condition, like ulcerative colitis or bacterial dysentery.\r\n\r\nMalabsorption syndrome: This can cause diarrhoea and weight loss, but bloody stools are not a common feature. The urgency and presence of blood in the stool point towards an inflammatory condition rather than malabsorption.\r\n\r\n\r\nUlcerative colitis is a chronic condition that leads to inflammation and ulceration of the colon, resulting in symptoms like bloody diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and urgency to defecate. According to NICE guidelines, management of ulcerative colitis depends on disease severity. Mild-to-moderate cases can often be managed with aminosalicylates like mesalazine, while more severe cases may require corticosteroids or immunosuppressants. Early diagnosis and appropriate treatment are essential to manage symptoms and prevent complications. Regular monitoring and tailored therapy are crucial for long-term disease control.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
