    "id": 2610,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 45 year old diabetic male presents to the pharmacy with a problem with his feet.\u00a0\r\nA picture of the patient's feet is presented below:\u00a0\r\n![fungalnail2](https://i.ibb.co/PDPhtzn/fungalnail2.jpg \"750x600\")",
    "why": "Patients with more than 2 nails affected and diabetic patients need to be referred.The most appropriate advice for the patient is:\r\n\r\n\"Advise to see his GP as soon as possible.\"\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nFor a diabetic patient presenting with a foot problem, it is crucial to prioritise proper assessment and management due to the increased risk of complications associated with diabetes, such as peripheral neuropathy and poor circulation. Fungal nail infections (onychomycosis) in diabetic patients can escalate quickly if left untreated and may lead to more severe complications like cellulitis or ulceration.\r\n\r\nAdvise the condition is self-limiting: This is not appropriate because fungal infections in diabetic patients are not typically self-limiting and require medical intervention.\r\nAdvise to purchase amorolfine 5% nail lacquer: While this is a suitable option for non-diabetic patients with mild fungal infections, it is insufficient for a diabetic patient who may need more thorough evaluation and management.\r\nAdvise to go to accident and emergency: This is not necessary unless the patient shows signs of severe infection, such as fever, spreading redness, or an open wound.\r\nSupply terbinafine 250mg tablets: Oral antifungals may be necessary, but they should only be supplied after proper assessment and prescription by a healthcare professional, especially considering potential contraindications or drug interactions in diabetic patients.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance for Diabetic Foot Health\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines emphasise that any foot issue in diabetic patients should be taken seriously and assessed promptly by a healthcare professional, as they are at a higher risk for complications. Diabetic patients with foot infections or ulcers should receive comprehensive management, including monitoring of blood glucose levels, appropriate antifungal or antibacterial treatment, and wound care if necessary.\r\n\r\nImportant Advice for Diabetic Patients with Foot Problems\r\nEarly Intervention: Diabetic individuals should seek medical advice immediately if they notice any changes in their feet, such as redness, swelling, infection, or abnormal nail appearance.\r\n\r\nFoot Hygiene and Care: Regularly inspect and clean feet, ensuring they are dried properly, particularly between the toes. Moisturisers may be used to prevent dry and cracked skin, but they should not be applied between the toes to avoid excess moisture.\r\nFootwear: Properly fitted shoes are essential to prevent trauma and reduce the risk of injury. Diabetic patients are also advised to wear cotton socks that allow feet to breathe.\r\nSpecialist Referral: Diabetic patients may be referred to a podiatrist or diabetic foot clinic for further evaluation and management, especially if the infection does not respond to initial treatments.\r\n\r\nBy following NICE guidelines and seeking timely medical advice, diabetic patients can minimise the risk of complications and maintain foot health effectively.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch BNF lesson chapter 6 Endocrine system\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
