    "id": 2588,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most likely diagnosis and the most appropriate treatment for this patient?**",
    "text": "A 50-year-old man presents to the pharmacy with a rash on his arms and legs, accompanied by itching and redness. He informs you he works as a cleaner.  He has no known allergies and is not currently taking any medication. He asks you for advice on how to treat his condition. ![acd2-Watermarked-Wy-JXYXRlcm1hcmtl-ZCJd](https://i.ibb.co/hYg4h12/acd2-Watermarked-Wy-JXYXRlcm1hcmtl-ZCJd.jpg \"650x500\")",
    "why": "Contact dermatitis; topical corticosteroids\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nThe most likely diagnosis in this case is contact dermatitis due to the patient's occupation as a cleaner, which increases exposure to irritants and allergens, such as cleaning agents. The patient's symptoms of itching, redness, and a rash on the arms and legs are typical signs of contact dermatitis.\r\n\r\nEczema is less likely since the symptoms appear to be triggered by an external factor, and the patient has no history of atopic conditions.\r\nHives are generally raised, itchy welts rather than a red, inflamed rash.\r\nPsoriasis tends to cause thick, silvery scales on the skin, not just redness and itching.\r\nScabies causes intense itching, particularly at night, and is usually associated with small burrows in the skin.\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, contact dermatitis is an inflammatory skin reaction that occurs when the skin is exposed to irritants or allergens. There are two types: irritant contact dermatitis, caused by substances that physically damage the skin, and allergic contact dermatitis, triggered by an immune response to specific allergens. \r\nSymptoms include redness, itching, swelling, and dry or cracked skin, usually in areas frequently exposed to the irritant or allergen.\r\n\r\nNICE recommends using topical corticosteroids as the first-line treatment to reduce inflammation and soothe symptoms. Additionally, emollients should be used regularly to maintain the skin's moisture barrier and prevent further irritation. It is essential for the patient to identify and avoid the causative irritant or allergen for long-term management. If symptoms persist or are severe, referral to a specialist may be necessary.**Image reference: DermnetNZ.org**\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
    "correct_answer_number": 1,
    "weighting": 3,
    "answers": [
      {
        "text": "Contact dermatitis; topical corticosteroids",
        "answer_number": 1
      },
      {
        "text": "Eczema; emollients and topical corticosteroids",
        "answer_number": 2
      },
      {
        "text": "Hives; antihistamines",
        "answer_number": 3
      },
      {
        "text": "Psoriasis; topical corticosteroids",
        "answer_number": 4
      },
      {
        "text": "Scabies; permethrin cream",
        "answer_number": 5
      }
    ],
