    "why": "A red flag referral is a symptom or sign that indicates a high risk of serious illness in a child with fever\u2074.\r\n- According to the NICE traffic light system for identifying risk of serious illness in under 5s\u00b2, some of the red flag features are:\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Age <3 months, temperature \u226538\u00b0C\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Non-blanching rash\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Bulging fontanelle\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Neck stiffness\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Status epilepticus\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Focal neurological signs\r\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0- Focal seizures\r\npost immunisation fever is a common and expected reaction to some vaccinations, especially in children aged under 3 months\u00b2. Post immunisation fever usually resolves within 48 hours and does not indicate a serious infection",
