    "text": "A 38 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy requesting to purchase Pyrocalm 20mg tablets for the treatment of dyspepsia. She informs you she is concerned regarding some of the side effects as her friend told her it can cause blood disorders.\u00a0\r\n\r\nThe SmPC for pyrocalm 20mg tablets has been provided for you\r\n\r\n\r\n[SmPC for Pyrocalm 20mg](https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/product/9154/smpc#gref)",
    "why": "(\u22651/10,000 to <1/1,000)\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Summary of Product Characteristics (SmPC) for Pyrocalm 20 mg tablets (omeprazole), thrombocytopenia is a rare side effect, occurring with a frequency between 1 in 10,000 and 1 in 1,000. Although this side effect is rare, patients should be aware of the potential risk and be advised to monitor for any signs of abnormal bruising or bleeding, which may indicate thrombocytopenia. Regular monitoring and reporting of unusual side effects are crucial, especially for those on long-term proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, PPIs like omeprazole are generally safe and well-tolerated treatments for dyspepsia. However, rare side effects such as thrombocytopenia can occur. NICE emphasizes the importance of regular treatment reviews, particularly for patients on long-term PPI therapy, to ensure the benefits continue to outweigh the risks. Patients should be informed about the possibility of rare side effects and encouraged to report any unusual symptoms promptly.\r\n\r\nThe initial management of dyspepsia focuses on lifestyle modifications, including changes to diet, reducing alcohol intake, avoiding known irritants like caffeine and spicy foods, quitting smoking, and maintaining a healthy weight. If these measures do not adequately control symptoms, pharmacological interventions are recommended, with proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) such as omeprazole being the first-line treatment to reduce stomach acid and provide symptom relief. Though PPIs are generally well-tolerated, they can occasionally cause rare side effects, such as thrombocytopenia (a blood disorder). Therefore, regular review of treatment effectiveness and close monitoring, especially for those on long-term PPI therapy, are essential to ensure the benefits outweigh the risks. Patients should be informed to report any unusual symptoms, particularly signs related to blood disorders like unexplained bruising or bleeding.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
