    "title": "**Which of the following medicines is NOT under safe custody regulations?**",
    "text": "The safe custody regulations refer to physical security of some controlled medicines.",
    "why": "B) Midazolam 5mg/ml ampoules\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nMidazolam is classified as a Schedule 3 controlled drug, and while it is a controlled substance, Schedule 3 drugs are not subject to the Safe Custody Regulations unless in injectable form. As such, midazolam 5mg/ml ampoules do not need to be stored under the stringent security measures required for Schedule 2 drugs. The Safe Custody Regulations apply only to Schedule 2 controlled drugs and certain Schedule 3 drugs with high misuse potential.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Buprenorphine 2mg sublingual tablets\r\n\r\nCorrect: Buprenorphine is a Schedule 3 controlled drug, but as it has significant misuse potential, it is subject to Safe Custody Regulations. Therefore, it must be stored securely.\r\n\r\nC) Morphine sulfate 10mg/1ml ampoules\r\n\r\nCorrect: Morphine sulfate is a Schedule 2 controlled drug, which is subject to the Safe Custody Regulations. Schedule 2 drugs require storage in a locked cabinet or safe.\r\n\r\nD) Oramorph 20mg/5ml oral solution\r\n\r\nCorrect: Oramorph is a Schedule 2 controlled drug. Like other Schedule 2 substances, it must be stored in secure conditions as per the Safe Custody Regulations.\r\n\r\nE) Temazepam 20mg tablets\r\n\r\nCorrect: Temazepam is classified as a Schedule 3 controlled drug and, due to its misuse potential, is subject to the Safe Custody Regulations. It must be securely stored in the pharmacy.\r\n\r\nThe Safe Custody Regulations require that specific controlled substances be stored securely to prevent misuse and diversion.\r\n\r\nSchedule 2 controlled drugs, such as morphine and Oramorph, must be stored in a locked cupboard or safe.\r\nCertain Schedule 3 drugs, such as buprenorphine and temazepam, also fall under the Safe Custody Regulations due to their misuse potential and must be securely stored.\r\nMidazolam 5mg/ml ampoules, although a Schedule 3 drug, do not require secure storage under the Safe Custody Regulations unless in injectable form.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
