    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A 23 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy with dysuria and discomfort. She explains her symptoms have been gradual in onset as well as vaginal discharge and pyuria.",
    "why": "### Chlamydia Overview \r\n\r\nChlamydia, caused by the bacterium *Chlamydia trachomatis*, is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI). Many people with chlamydia are asymptomatic, especially in the early stages. When symptoms do occur, they may include:\r\n\r\n- **Painful Urination**: A burning sensation during urination.\r\n- **Abnormal Vaginal or Penile Discharge**: Unusual discharge from the vagina or penis.\r\n- **Pelvic or Lower Abdominal Pain**: Women may experience pelvic pain, while men may have testicular discomfort.\r\n- **Painful Intercourse**: Women may experience discomfort during sex.\r\n- **Bleeding Between Periods**: Women may notice abnormal bleeding between menstrual periods.\r\n- **Rectal Symptoms**: Rectal pain, discharge, or bleeding if the infection affects the rectum.\r\n\r\n### Genital Chlamydia Infection \r\n\r\n- **Prevalence**: Chlamydia is the most common bacterial STI in the UK.\r\n- **Affected Areas**: Typically infects the urethra in men, and the cervix or urethra in women. It can also affect the conjunctiva, rectum, and nasopharynx.\r\n- **Asymptomatic Rates**: 70% of women and 50% of men show no symptoms.\r\n\r\n### Screening & Testing\r\n\r\n- **Screening**: \r\n  - Annual screening is recommended for sexually active people under 25 or those with frequent partner changes.\r\n  \r\n- **Testing**:\r\n  - **Women**: Vulvo-vaginal swab is preferred. Alternatives include an endocervical swab or first-void urine sample.\r\n  - **Men**: First-void urine is the sample of choice, but a urethral swab is an option.\r\n\r\n### Treatment\r\n\r\n- **First-line**: Doxycycline 100 mg twice daily for 7 days.\r\n- **Pregnancy/Breastfeeding**: After consulting a specialist, azithromycin, amoxicillin, or erythromycin may be considered.\r\n\r\n### Management\r\n\r\n- Referral to a Genito-Urinary Medicine (GUM) clinic is recommended for treatment and partner notification. If GUM referral is not possible, primary care can manage the condition.\r\n- Educate on STI transmission and risk reduction. Sexual activity should be avoided until treatment completion.\r\n  \r\n### Follow-up\r\n\r\n- **Test of Cure**: Not usually necessary but recommended during pregnancy or if symptoms persist.\r\n- **Repeat Testing**: Advised 3\u20136 months post-treatment for under-25s or those at high risk of reinfection.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 6 Gynaecology:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
