    "text": "**Theme: Timeframes**\r\n\r\n**For the following descriptions, please select the most suitable validity period of prescriptions from or after the appropriate date, from the list provided.\r\nEach option may be used once, more than once, or not at all.**",
    "why": "Correct Answer: \r\n\r\nD) 6 months\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\n- Veterinary prescriptions, including those issued under the Cascade for unlicensed use of human medicines like fluoxetine, are legally valid for 6 months from the appropriate date, unless they involve Schedule 2, 3 or 4 controlled drugs, in which case the validity is 28 days.\r\n\r\n- Since fluoxetine is not a controlled drug, the standard validity of 6 months applies.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) 7 days \u2013 Used for veterinary Schedule 2 or 3 controlled drugs, not applicable here.\r\n\r\nB) 28 days \u2013 Only applies to CDs Schedule 2\u20134, not to fluoxetine.\r\n\r\nC) 30 days \u2013 Not a recognised timeframe for veterinary prescriptions.\r\n\r\nE\u2013H (2 years to 10 years) \u2013 Refer to record retention timeframes, not prescription validity.\r\n\r\n\r\nAlthough NICE guidelines primarily cover human prescribing, the Veterinary Medicines Regulations (VMR) govern the validity of veterinary prescriptions. According to VMR, a prescription for a POM-V medicine or a human medicine prescribed under the Cascade is valid for 6 months, unless it contains a controlled drug, in which case the validity is reduced to 28 days.\r\n\r\nPharmacists supplying veterinary medicines must check prescription details carefully, especially when dispensing human medicines for animal use, and record them appropriately.\r\n\r\nFor more information, please watch MEP (Chapter 2) Professional and Legal Issues:\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
