    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate advice?**",
    "text": "A mother presents to the pharmacy with her 8 year old son. She informs you her son has been diagnosed with ADHD. Her son takes Concerta (methylphenidate) 18mg tablets and has been struggling to sleep.",
    "why": "Her son is experiencing a side effect of methylphenidate, and whilst safe to continue taking it, she may wish to see the specialist for insomnia treatment.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nRecognising Side Effects: Methylphenidate (Concerta) is known to cause side effects, including insomnia and difficulties with sleep, particularly when taken later in the day. It is important to recognise that this can be a common side effect of stimulant medications used to treat ADHD.\r\n\r\nSafety of Continuing Medication: The advice indicates that while insomnia is a recognised side effect, it is generally safe to continue taking methylphenidate. Stopping the medication abruptly is not typically recommended without consulting the prescribing healthcare provider.\r\n\r\nReferral to Specialist: The best course of action is to advise the mother to consult with the specialist or the child\u2019s prescribing physician to discuss the insomnia. The healthcare provider can assess the situation and potentially recommend adjustments to the medication regimen or suggest appropriate treatments for managing insomnia, such as behavioural interventions or sleep hygiene practices.\r\n\r\nOther Options:\r\n\r\nPhenergan (Promethazine) and Diphenhydramine: While these medications can cause sedation, they are not typically recommended for managing insomnia in children with ADHD, as they may not address the underlying issue and could introduce additional side effects. Moreover, the long-term use of antihistamines in children is generally discouraged.\r\nStopping Methylphenidate: Stopping the medication outright without discussing it with a healthcare provider could lead to a return of ADHD symptoms, which is not ideal.\r\nInformation on ADHD in Children:\r\nAccording to the NICE guidelines, Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a neurodevelopment disorder characterised by persistent patterns of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity that interfere with functioning or development. The guidelines outline the following key points regarding the assessment and management of ADHD in children:\r\n\r\nDiagnosis: The diagnosis of ADHD should be based on a comprehensive assessment that includes gathering information from multiple sources, such as parents, teachers, and the child. The symptoms must be present in multiple settings (e.g., at home and school) and significantly impact the child's daily functioning.\r\n\r\nManagement:\r\n\r\nBehavioural Interventions: Non-pharmacological approaches, such as parent training in behaviour management and school-based interventions, should be offered as first-line treatment, especially for preschool-aged children.\r\nPharmacological Treatment: For children aged 5 years and older with moderate to severe ADHD symptoms that do not respond adequately to behavioural interventions, pharmacological treatment may be considered. Stimulants, such as methylphenidate (Concerta), are often the first-line medications, with careful monitoring for side effects, including insomnia.\r\nMonitoring and Follow-Up: Regular follow-up is essential to evaluate the effectiveness of treatment and adjust as needed. The healthcare provider should monitor for side effects, growth, and overall well-being. If insomnia or other side effects arise, a reassessment of the medication regimen may be warranted.\r\n\r\nCoexisting Conditions: Many children with ADHD may have coexisting conditions, such as anxiety or learning disabilities. The guidelines emphasise the need for a holistic approach to care that addresses these additional challenges.\r\n\r\nEducation and Support: Parents and caregivers should be provided with information and support regarding ADHD to help them understand the condition and its management better. Engaging with educational resources and support groups can also be beneficial for families.\r\n\r\nFor more informatio watch BNF lesson chapter 4 (ADHD):\r\n\r\n(https://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course)",
