    "title": "**Which ONE of the following statements is CORRECT regarding pseudoephedrine?**",
    "text": "A 43-year-old female patient presenting in your pharmacy with nasal congestion and would like to purchase some decongestants",
    "why": "C. She can purchase a maximum legal quantity of 720mg of pseudoephedrine.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to UK regulations, pseudoephedrine-containing products can only be sold in limited quantities. The maximum legal quantity that can be sold without a prescription is 720 mg. This limit applies to any combination of products containing pseudoephedrine or ephedrine in a single transaction.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA. Pseudoephedrine-containing medicines can only be sold either by the Pharmacist or under supervision of the responsible pharmacist:\r\nThis is incorrect. While pseudoephedrine is a regulated substance and must be sold under supervision, it is not specifically restricted to only being sold by the pharmacist or under their direct supervision. As long as the responsible pharmacist is available, others can assist with the sale, but it must be done in accordance with legal requirements, such as limiting the quantity sold.\r\n\r\nB. She can purchase a maximum legal quantity of 180mg of pseudoephedrine:\r\nThis is incorrect. The maximum legal quantity is 720 mg, not 180 mg. The 180 mg limit applies to ephedrine, not pseudoephedrine.\r\n\r\nD. She can purchase one packet of pseudoephedrine for herself and the other packet for her daughter:\r\nThis is incorrect. The legal limit of 720 mg applies to the total amount of pseudoephedrine being sold in a single transaction. A customer cannot buy multiple packets that, together, exceed the 720 mg limit.\r\n\r\nE. She can purchase two separate products which containing pseudoephedrine and the other phenylephrine:\r\nThis is incorrect. While phenylephrine is a common decongestant, it does not count toward the limit on pseudoephedrine. However, the key point here is that the law limits the total amount of pseudoephedrine in a single transaction, not phenylephrine. If the total amount of pseudoephedrine from the products exceeds 720 mg, it would be illegal.\r\n\r\nPseudoephedrine is a regulated substance due to its potential for misuse in the production of illicit drugs. As per UK regulations, the maximum legal quantity of pseudoephedrine that can be sold without a prescription is 720 mg. Any sales exceeding this limit must be prescribed by a doctor. Additionally, sales of pseudoephedrine-containing products must be controlled to ensure the amount sold in any given transaction does not exceed legal thresholds. Pharmacists are responsible for ensuring that sales comply with these regulations to prevent misuse while ensuring that legitimate patients have access to the medication they need for conditions like nasal congestion.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
