    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "You are the responsible pharmacist and you receive a Welsh prescription written in Welsh. You do not speak Welsh",
    "why": "d) Use a translation service such as Language Line and write the dispensing label in English as you are a non-Welsh speaker\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nWhen presented with a Welsh prescription and the pharmacist does not understand the language, patient safety is the priority. Using a recognised translation service ensures accurate interpretation of the prescription. Writing the dispensing label in English minimises the risk of errors, as it allows the pharmacist to confidently verify the information. This approach complies with the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines for patient safety.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Google translate the prescription and write the dispensing instructions on the label in Welsh\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Using an unverified translation tool such as Google Translate poses a high risk of errors due to potential inaccuracies, which could compromise patient safety.\r\n\r\nb) Inform the patient you do not understand Welsh, therefore decline the prescription\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Pharmacists must take reasonable steps to assist patients, such as using professional translation services, rather than outright refusing service.\r\n\r\nc) It is illegal for you to dispense a prescription written in Welsh, therefore you refuse to dispense the medication\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Welsh prescriptions are legally valid within Wales. Declining to dispense such prescriptions without taking further action would be inappropriate and could lead to patient harm.\r\n\r\ne) Use a translation service such as Language Line and write the dispensing label in Welsh\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. As a non-Welsh-speaking pharmacist, you might not fully understand Welsh labels, which increases the risk of errors. Writing labels in English ensures you can review and verify the information.\r\n\r\n\r\nWelsh prescriptions are legally valid and recognised in Wales, and pharmacists must ensure they handle these appropriately to maintain patient safety. Key considerations include:\r\n\r\nTranslation services: Use reliable services such as Language Line to ensure accurate interpretation of prescriptions written in Welsh.\r\nDispensing labels: Non-Welsh-speaking pharmacists should write dispensing instructions in English to minimise errors.\r\nPatient communication: If clarification is required, discuss with the patient or prescriber in a respectful and professional manner.\r\nLegality: It is legal to dispense Welsh prescriptions, provided the pharmacist ensures accurate understanding of the instructions.\r\nBy following these steps, pharmacists can ensure safe and effective dispensing while meeting the needs of all patients.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 4 (The Responsible Pharmacist)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
