    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription for a 54-year-old male who has been prescribed gabapentin for monotherapy of focal seizures. Todays date is the 28th December 2023.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\n\r\n![2](https://i.ibb.co/MVKJ3jT/2.png)",
    "why": "(d) Refuse to dispense the prescription as it is not on a standardised form.\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nGabapentin is classified as a Schedule 3 controlled drug, which requires it to be prescribed on a standardised, approved form (such as the pink FP10PCD) to meet legal requirements for dispensing. The prescription provided does not meet this requirement, so dispensing is not permitted.\r\n\r\nRegarding other criteria:\r\n\r\nThe prescription is not out of date. For Schedule 3 controlled drugs, prescriptions remain valid for 28 days from the date on the prescription. \r\nSince today\u2019s date is 28th December, the prescription would remain valid until the following day, 29th December.\r\nThe quantity is correctly written in both words and figures, meaning no amendment is necessary.\r\nEmergency supply is not allowed for Schedule 3 controlled drugs (except for phenobarbital in the treatment of epilepsy), so an emergency supply cannot be provided in this case.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(a) Advise the patient to return to their consultant for a new prescription as it is out of date \u2013 Incorrect, as the prescription is still within the valid 28-day period.\r\n\r\n(b) Amend the quantity of the prescription to meet all legal requirements and then dispense the prescription \u2013 Incorrect, as the quantity is already written in both words and figures, so no amendment is needed.\r\n\r\n(c) Provide an emergency supply and request a new prescription from the consultant \u2013 Incorrect, as gabapentin cannot be supplied in an emergency.\r\n\r\n(e) The prescription meets all legal requirements therefore dispense the prescription \u2013 Incorrect, as it is not on the required standardised form.\r\n\r\nAs gabapentin is a Schedule 3 controlled drug, it must be prescribed on a standardised form for legal compliance. \r\nThe pharmacist cannot dispense this prescription as it lacks the required form and cannot be supplied in an emergency. \r\nThe patient should be informed and referred back to their prescriber for a valid prescription to ensure safe and lawful dispensing.\r\n\r\nWatch MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
