    "id": 2594,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's symptoms?**",
    "text": "A 21 year old female patient presents to the pharmacy with a new onset of abdominal discomfort. She informs you she is also experiencing heartburn which wakes her up at night and her stools have \u201ctar\u201d colour. She has no allergies. Her regular medication is below:\u00a0\r\n\r\nNaproxen 250mg tablets: Take one tablet three times a day\u00a0\r\nCitalopram 10mg tablets: Take one daily\u00a0\r\nFexofenadine 180mg tablets: Take one daily\u00a0\r\nMometasone 50mcg/dose nasal spray: Two sprays in each nostril once a day\u00a0\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n.",
    "why": "Duodenal or gastric bleed\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe patient's symptoms, including abdominal discomfort, heartburn, and tar-coloured stools (melena), strongly suggest the presence of a duodenal or gastric bleed. The dark, tarry appearance of the stools indicates the presence of digested blood, which typically originates from the upper gastrointestinal tract. The most common cause of such bleeding is an ulcer, often associated with the use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like naproxen, which the patient is taking regularly. NSAIDs are known to increase the risk of gastrointestinal bleeding by inhibiting the production of protective gastric mucosa.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nDuodenal or gastric ulcer: While ulcers could explain the abdominal discomfort and heartburn, the presence of melena (black, tarry stools) indicates that the ulcer has likely progressed to bleeding.\r\n\r\nFunctional dyspepsia: This could cause abdominal discomfort and heartburn, but it does not typically cause tarry stools, which suggest a gastrointestinal bleed.\r\n\r\nGastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD): GORD could explain the heartburn and discomfort, but tarry stools are not a common feature of reflux and suggest a more serious underlying condition like a bleed.\r\n\r\nIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS): IBS does not usually present with tarry stools or gastrointestinal bleeding, and its symptoms typically involve a pattern of bowel habit changes (diarrhoea or constipation) without the presence of melena.\r\n\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines highlight the risk of gastrointestinal bleeding associated with the use of NSAIDs such as naproxen, especially in individuals taking them regularly for pain or inflammation. These drugs can cause irritation and ulceration of the stomach lining, leading to symptoms like abdominal discomfort, heartburn, and serious complications such as bleeding. Patients at risk (e.g., those on long-term NSAIDs) should be monitored, and prophylactic treatment with proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) may be considered to reduce the risk of GI bleeding. Immediate referral is warranted if there are signs of bleeding, such as melena or hematemesis.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
    "correct_answer": null,
    "answer_unit": null,
