    "why": "Dietary advice\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor a pregnant woman experiencing hard, dry stools for the first time, dietary advice is the most appropriate first-step treatment. Recommendations may include increasing dietary fibre intake through fruits, vegetables, and whole grains, as well as ensuring adequate hydration. This approach is non-pharmacological and safer for both the mother and the developing fetus.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nBulk forming laxative: While these can help with constipation, dietary changes should be the first-line approach before introducing any medication.\r\n\r\nOsmotic laxative: These are effective for treating constipation, but they are generally considered after dietary changes do not provide relief.\r\n\r\nStimulant laxative: These should be avoided in the initial treatment of constipation, especially during pregnancy, due to potential adverse effects on bowel function.\r\n\r\nStool softener: Although useful, it is usually recommended after dietary modifications if symptoms persist.\r\n\r\n\r\nConstipation is a common issue during pregnancy due to hormonal changes, decreased physical activity, and pressure on the bowel from the growing uterus. NICE guidelines emphasise the importance of dietary modifications as a first-line intervention, encouraging increased fibre intake and hydration to manage constipation effectively. If dietary changes are insufficient, laxatives may be considered, but pregnant women should avoid certain types of laxatives, such as stimulants, to reduce the risk of complications. Regular monitoring and supportive care are essential to ensure maternal comfort and health.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 7 (Gastroenterology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
