    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**What is the most likely diagnosis and the most appropriate treatment for this patient?**",
    "text": "A 25-year-old woman presents to the pharmacy with a red, itchy and watery right eye. She says she woke up this morning with a sticky discharge on her eyelid and lashes. She has no history of eye problems or contact lens use. She is otherwise healthy and takes no medication. She asks you for advice on how to treat her condition.",
    "why": "This is because the patient has symptoms of acute bacterial conjunctivitis, such as redness, discharge, itching and crusting of the eyelids. Chloramphenicol eye drops are available over the counter for the treatment of bacterial conjunctivitis in adults and children over 2 years old.\r\n\r\n- Infective conjunctivitis is caused by viral, bacterial, or parasitic infections.\r\n- **Viral conjunctivitis** (mainly adenoviruses) is the most common type.\r\n- **Bacterial causes** include **Streptococcus pneumoniae**, **Staphylococcus aureus**, and **Haemophilus influenzae**.\r\n- **Hyperacute conjunctivitis** is a severe form caused by **Neisseria gonorrhoeae**.\r\n- **Ophthalmia neonatorum (ON)** affects newborns within the first four weeks of life and can be infectious or non-infectious.\r\n- Conjunctivitis is usually self-limiting; viral cases resolve in 7 days, bacterial in 5\u201310 days.\r\n- Contact lens wearers and immunocompromised people are at higher risk of complications.\r\n- Untreated ON can lead to severe complications like sight loss.\r\n- Symptoms include conjunctival redness, gritty or burning sensation, watering, and discharge.\r\n- Urgent referral to ophthalmology is needed for serious cases (e.g., ON, gonococcal or chlamydial infection, herpes, or severe disease).\r\n  \r\n**Primary care management:**\r\n- Reassure patients that most cases are self-limiting.\r\n- Advise self-care (cleaning eyelids, cool compresses, lubricating drops, avoid contact lenses).\r\n- Use antibiotics like **chloramphenicol** or **fusidic acid** for suspected bacterial infections.\r\n- Provide follow-up\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on  Chapter 3 Opthalmology and Otology (conjunctivitis) :\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
