    "id": 2581,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding the sale and supply of hydrocortisone 1% cream?**",
    "text": "A mother presents to the pharmacy with her 10 year old son. She explains her son suffers from atopic eczema. She is away from home visiting family and unable to get a GP appointment. She is wondering if it is possible to purchase a steroid cream over the counter.",
    "why": "b) Hydrocortisone is a low potency steroid therefore safe to use on the face\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis statement is incorrect because, while hydrocortisone 1% is a low-potency steroid, it is generally not recommended for use on the face without medical supervision. The facial skin is particularly sensitive, and prolonged or unsupervised use of steroids in this area can lead to adverse effects such as skin thinning, perioral dermatitis, or worsening of skin sensitivity.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Options:\r\n\r\na) Hydrocortisone can be sold to those 10 years and older for the treatment of eczema\r\n\r\nOver-the-counter regulations allow hydrocortisone 1% cream to be sold for children aged 10 and above to treat mild cases of eczema.\r\n\r\nc) Hydrocortisone must not be used on broken or infected skin\r\n\r\nIt is important to avoid applying hydrocortisone on broken or infected skin, as this can exacerbate infection risks and increase sensitivity in those areas.\r\n\r\nd) Hydrocortisone can be used once or twice a day\r\n\r\nThe standard recommendation is to apply hydrocortisone 1% cream once or twice daily to manage symptoms such as inflammation and itching for short-term use.\r\n\r\ne) Maximum treatment duration is for one week\r\n\r\nTo reduce the risk of side effects, it is advised that hydrocortisone 1% cream be used for no longer than one week for self-treatment purposes.\r\n\r\n\r\nAtopic eczema is a chronic, inflammatory skin condition characterized by dry, itchy, and inflamed skin. According to NICE guidelines, the mainstays of treatment are regular emollient use to maintain skin hydration and topical corticosteroids for flare-ups to manage inflammation and itching. Emollients should be applied frequently, even when the skin appears clear, to prevent flare-ups. NICE also advises parents and caregivers to avoid known triggers and keep nails short to minimize skin damage from scratching. For severe or persistent cases, referral to a healthcare professional is recommended to consider additional treatments or alternative management options.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
