    "text": "A 45 year old male presents to the pharmacy requesting to purchase Viagra Connect. He informs you he has tadalafil 10mg tablets prescribed however he has run out. The Pharmacy checklist has been provided for you.",
    "why": "a) Refuse the sale and refer the patient to his GP for a prescription of tadalafil 10mg tablets.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nSince the patient is currently prescribed tadalafil 10mg by his GP, it's important to advise him to consult his GP for a new prescription rather than switching to over-the-counter (OTC) sildenafil (Viagra Connect). This ensures continuity of treatment and confirms that the medication he is taking is appropriate for his current health status.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(b) Sell Viagra Connect and inform the patient they must see their GP within 6 months:\r\nIncorrect. Since the patient is on a prescribed medication (tadalafil) for erectile dysfunction, selling Viagra Connect would be inappropriate without consulting the GP, as it could interfere with the prescribed treatment plan.\r\n\r\n(c) Sell Viagra Connect and inform the patient they must see their GP for a new prescription:\r\nIncorrect. While this option addresses the need for a follow-up with the GP, switching him to Viagra Connect without consultation may affect his current treatment with tadalafil.\r\n\r\n(d) Sell Viagra Connect as long as nothing has changed with respect to his health status or medicines usage:\r\nIncorrect. Even if there are no changes in his health status, the patient\u2019s current medication (tadalafil) is GP-prescribed, and it is preferable to continue with his current treatment plan under medical supervision.\r\n\r\n(e) Sell Viagra Connect as there is no need to repeat the questioning as treatment was already prescribed by his GP:\r\nIncorrect. Though he has a prescription for erectile dysfunction treatment, the medication prescribed (tadalafil) differs from sildenafil (Viagra Connect). Confirming suitability through his GP is essential to ensure safe and effective treatment.\r\n\r\nTadalafil is available over the counter (OTC) in some formulations and countries, though it often requires consultation with a pharmacist. In the UK, for instance, tadalafil 10mg has been made available OTC under the brand name Cialis Daily, but typically this applies only to lower dosages and requires pharmacist assessment to ensure safety. Higher doses or longer-acting versions of tadalafil (like the 10mg and 20mg) are generally prescription-only due to increased risk of side effects and contraindications, particularly when there are underlying health concerns.\r\n\r\nIn the scenario given:\r\n\r\nSince the patient is already on tadalafil 10mg via prescription, it\u2019s best practice to maintain consistency with his prescribed medication rather than switching to OTC sildenafil (Viagra Connect). This minimizes risk and ensures optimal management, as the GP can reassess the need and dosage.\r\n\r\nIf the patient requires tadalafil urgently and no GP appointment is available, he may discuss OTC tadalafil availability with the pharmacist. However, switching medications without professional guidance, especially in cases of erectile dysfunction, can affect efficacy and safety.\r\n\r\nIn such cases, referring the patient back to the GP or consulting with them regarding OTC tadalafil options would be prudent.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson Chapter 9 (Reclassified Medicines)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
