    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "A 15 year old female presents to the pharmacy and she is feeling a bit embarrassed as she is experiencing a few acne spots on her face. She has had it for three weeks and is desperate to try something over the counter. She does not wear too much make up and is currently using a mild cleanser both morning and evening. She is on no other medication.",
    "why": "b) Offer Benzoyl Peroxide 5% gel over the counter with counselling\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nBenzoyl Peroxide 5% gel is an effective and commonly recommended over-the-counter (OTC) treatment for mild acne, especially for teenage patients. Benzoyl peroxide has both antibacterial and comedolytic properties, helping to reduce acne-causing bacteria on the skin and unclog pores. It is generally considered the first-line treatment for mild acne and can be used safely in young patients. The patient should be advised on potential side effects, such as skin dryness and irritation, and should start with a small amount to assess tolerance. She should also be reminded to use sunscreen as benzoyl peroxide may increase photosensitivity.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Options\r\n\r\na) Advise the patient to carry on using a mild cleanser twice a day\r\n\r\nAlthough continuing with a mild cleanser is beneficial, it may not be sufficient to address her acne. Benzoyl peroxide would be more effective for active treatment.\r\n\r\nb) Offer Benzoyl Peroxide 5% gel over the counter with counselling\r\n\r\nThis is the most appropriate action, as benzoyl peroxide is effective for mild acne and can be recommended as an OTC option. Proper counselling on usage, possible irritation, and the need for sun protection makes this a suitable first step in treating her acne.\r\n\r\nc) No treatment is required the condition will improve with age\r\n\r\nWhile acne may lessen over time, starting an OTC treatment like benzoyl peroxide can help manage her symptoms more effectively now and improve her confidence.\r\n\r\nd) Recommend Nicotinamide gel due to its anti-inflammatory effect\r\n\r\nNicotinamide (or niacinamide) gel is sometimes used in acne treatment due to its anti-inflammatory effects, but benzoyl peroxide is more effective as a first-line option. Additionally, nicotinamide gel is not commonly available OTC for acne.\r\n\r\ne) Refer to the GP as it could be something else\r\n\r\nSince this case presents as mild acne, referral to a GP is unnecessary at this stage. OTC treatment is typically the initial approach.\r\n\r\n\r\nAcne vulgaris is a common skin condition, particularly in adolescents, characterised by comedones (blackheads and whiteheads), papules, and pustules. NICE guidelines recommend beginning treatment with topical agents, such as benzoyl peroxide, for mild cases. Benzoyl peroxide is available OTC and is often the first-line treatment due to its dual action in reducing bacteria and helping to clear blocked pores.\r\n\r\nGuidelines also suggest lifestyle support, such as gentle cleansing routines and avoiding products that might clog pores. If OTC treatments are ineffective or acne worsens, a healthcare provider may recommend additional treatments, including topical retinoids or antibiotics.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
