    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a red flag referral for patients suffering with haemorrhoids?**",
    "text": "You are teaching your trainee pharmacist about haemorrhoids.",
    "why": "The option that is NOT a red flag referral for patients suffering with haemorrhoids is:\r\n\r\nA 39 year old with no persistent change in bowel habits.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nA 39-year-old patient with haemorrhoids and no persistent change in bowel habits does not present any red flag symptoms. This indicates the absence of more serious underlying conditions, such as colorectal cancer or inflammatory bowel disease. Haemorrhoids can occur without changes in bowel habits, and this symptom alone is not concerning if other warning signs are absent.\r\n\r\nA 63-year-old patient with blood mixed in the stool: This is a red flag symptom, as blood mixed in the stool rather than on its surface could suggest a more serious condition such as colorectal cancer. Immediate referral to a GP is necessary.\r\n\r\nA 24-year-old who has severe pain on defecation: Severe pain could indicate complications such as thrombosed haemorrhoids or an anal fissure. Referral may be necessary for further assessment.\r\n\r\nA 55-year-old who has unexplained rectal bleeding: Unexplained rectal bleeding in a patient over 50 is considered a red flag and should be referred for further investigation to rule out serious pathology.\r\n\r\nA 74-year-old patient who needs to reduce their haemorrhoids manually: This suggests prolapsed haemorrhoids that are not resolving on their own. In elderly patients, it is especially important to rule out more severe conditions.\r\n\r\nNICE Guidance on Haemorrhoids and Red Flag Symptoms\r\n\r\nNICE guidelines for the management of haemorrhoids include recognising red flag symptoms that warrant referral:\r\n\r\nRectal Bleeding:\r\n\r\nPatients over 50 years old with new-onset or unexplained rectal bleeding should be referred for further investigation, as it could be a sign of colorectal cancer.\r\n\r\nBlood mixed in the stool is also a red flag, as it may indicate bleeding higher up in the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nPersistent Change in Bowel Habits:\r\n\r\nAny persistent change in bowel habits, particularly diarrhoea or constipation lasting more than 6 weeks, should prompt further investigation in patients over 40.\r\nSevere Pain or Prolapse:\r\n\r\nSevere pain during defecation, especially if associated with swelling or a prolapsed haemorrhoid, may require medical intervention.\r\n\r\nHaemorrhoids that prolapse and need to be manually reduced should be assessed by a healthcare provider.\r\n\r\nWeight Loss or Anemia:\r\n\r\nUnexplained weight loss, fatigue, or signs of anemia alongside haemorrhoids are also red flags that necessitate referral.\r\n\r\nAdditional Insights\r\n\r\nHaemorrhoids are a common condition that can cause discomfort and bleeding, but they are generally benign. However, it is essential to identify any red flags that could suggest more severe underlying conditions. Patients should be educated on the importance of recognising symptoms such as persistent changes in bowel habits, blood mixed in stool, and severe pain, as these may require further medical evaluation.\r\n\r\nPreventive advice for haemorrhoids includes maintaining a high-fibre diet, adequate hydration, and avoiding straining during bowel movements. For patients without red flags, over-the-counter treatments like topical creams, warm baths, and lifestyle modifications can effectively manage symptoms. If symptoms do not improve, or if any concerning signs develop, patients should be advised to seek medical attention promptly.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson chapter 7 Gastroenterology (haemorrhoids):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
