    "why": "Infantile colic. The infant has classic symptoms of infantile colic, which is a common and benign condition that affects up to 20% of infants in the first three months of life\u00b9. Infantile colic is defined as recurrent and prolonged episodes of crying, fussing, or irritability in an otherwise healthy and well-fed infant, without an obvious cause\u00b9. The exact cause of infantile colic is unknown, but it may be related to immature gastrointestinal function, altered gut microbiota, excessive gas production, hypersensitivity to stimuli, or psychosocial factors\u00b9. Infantile colic usually resolves spontaneously by 4-6 months of age\u00b9.",
