    "id": 2632,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most likely cause of the child's symptoms?**",
    "text": "A mother brings her 4 year old daughter into your pharmacy because she is concerned about a rash. The mother explains her daughter has not been well over the past few days and has\u00a0 noticed there were white spots in the mouth before the rash appeared.\u00a0\r\n\r\nA photograph of the rash has been shown below:\u00a0\r\n\r\n\r\n![measles08-Watermarked-Wy-JXYXRlcm1hcmtl-ZCJd-2](https://i.ibb.co/WGy9fJT/measles08-Watermarked-Wy-JXYXRlcm1hcmtl-ZCJd-2.jpg)",
    "why": "Measles is a highly contagious airborne infection caused by a morbillivirus from the paramyxovirus family. It spreads through the respiratory tract and infects nearly all susceptible individuals, providing lifelong immunity once contracted. While measles was once endemic in the UK, it has become rare due to immunisation.\r\n\r\n**Complications** primarily affect the respiratory system and central nervous system, including:\r\n- Otitis media.\r\n- Pneumonia, pneumonitis, and tracheobronchitis.\r\n- Convulsions, encephalitis, and blindness.\r\n- Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (a rare but serious complication affecting 1 in 25,000).\r\n\r\nMeasles is often more severe in adults, infants, immunocompromised individuals, and during pregnancy. Symptoms usually resolve within a week, but complications may occur. Early signs (prodromal stage) include fever, cough, coryza (cold-like symptoms), and conjunctivitis, followed by a characteristic maculopapular rash and possibly Koplik\u2019s spots in the mouth. \r\n\r\n**Differential diagnoses** for measles include:\r\n- Parvovirus B19 (fifth disease or slapped cheek syndrome).\r\n- Scarlet fever.\r\n- Roseola infantum.\r\n- Rubella.\r\n- Kawasaki disease.\r\n- Early meningococcal disease.\r\n\r\nMeasles is a notifiable disease, and suspected cases must be reported to the local Health Protection Team (HPT). Treatment mainly involves rest, fluid intake, and paracetamol or ibuprofen for symptom relief. Those with measles should stay away from nursery, school, or work for four days after the rash develops and avoid contact with vulnerable individuals, including unvaccinated people, pregnant women, and those who are immunocompromised.\r\n\r\nSpecialist advice is essential for those at higher risk, such as pregnant women, infants, or immunocompromised individuals who have been in contact with someone with measles. Hospital admission may be necessary if complications arise, such as pneumonia or neurological issues like encephalitis or febrile convulsions.\r\n\r\n**Stages of measles:**\r\n- **Prodromal stage:** High fever (38.3\u201340\u00b0C), cough, Koplik's spots in the mouth (though not always present), coryza, and conjunctivitis.\r\n- **Rash stage:** A red, blotchy maculopapular rash begins on the face and spreads downwards to the body. Other symptoms may include conjunctivitis, light sensitivity, and general malaise.\r\n**Image reference: DermnetNZ.org**\r\n\r\nFor more information watch the OTC lesson on Chapter 1 Paediatrics (Measles):\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
