    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a record requirement for signed orders?**",
    "text": "Schools can obtain adrenaline auto injections and/or salbutamol on signed order for emergency treatment for pupils previously prescribed these medicines",
    "why": "D) Pharmacist name and address supplying the medicine\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe name and address of the pharmacist supplying the medicine are not required as part of the record for a signed order. The signed order record focuses on details necessary to trace the supplied medication, confirm its use, and document relevant patient and supply information, rather than the specifics of the pharmacist's identity or business address.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Date of POM supplied \u2013 This is a required record detail, as it documents when the prescription-only medicine (POM) was supplied. Recording the supply date is essential for tracking and verifying the timing of medication provision for school emergencies.\r\n\r\nB) Name and address of business or profession to whom medicine is supplied to \u2013 This is a required detail, ensuring that the medicine is being supplied to a legitimate recipient, such as a school. This information allows traceability and accountability, confirming the medicine\u2019s intended destination.\r\n\r\nC) Name and quantity of medicine supplied \u2013 Recording the name and quantity of the medicine supplied is necessary for clarity and verification of the type and amount of medication provided, which is critical for accurate inventory and regulatory compliance.\r\n\r\nE) Purpose of signed order \u2013 The purpose of the signed order must be documented, confirming that the medication is intended for emergency use for pupils previously prescribed the treatment. This detail helps ensure that the medication is used correctly and supports its intended purpose in an emergency situation.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Medicines, Ethics and Practice (MEP) guidelines outline specific requirements for signed orders to ensure safe and accountable medication provision in schools. When schools obtain emergency medicines, such as adrenaline auto-injectors or salbutamol inhalers, a record must include the date of supply, the name and address of the receiving institution, the name and quantity of medicine supplied, and the intended purpose of the medication. These requirements allow for clear tracking and traceability, confirming that these medicines are held securely and used appropriately in school emergencies.\r\n\r\nHowever, the name and address of the supplying pharmacist are not part of the legal requirements. The MEP guidelines prioritise details directly related to patient safety and regulatory compliance, focusing on the purpose, recipient, and medication specifics to ensure that schools can access emergency treatments safely and responsibly without unnecessary administrative burdens.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
