    "id": 2570,
    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "A four-year-old child who presents with an itchy, red vesicular rash, which has been present for the last two days, since he came home from nursery. The rash is apparent on his torso and face.",
    "text": "**Theme: Dermatological preparations**\r\n\r\n**For each of the following scenarios select the best option for over-the-counter treatment. Each option may be used once, more than once or not at all.**",
    "why": "b) Aqueous calamine cream\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAqueous calamine cream is the best choice for this four-year-old child, as it provides a soothing effect and helps to relieve itching commonly associated with vesicular rashes. Calamine is especially suitable for children due to its gentle action, and it is generally well-tolerated on sensitive skin areas like the face and torso. This product also helps to cool and mildly dry the vesicles, offering temporary relief without introducing any steroids, which are typically avoided in very young children without a prescription.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\na) Aloe vera gel: Although soothing, aloe vera lacks the anti-itching effects needed for a vesicular rash and may be insufficient for symptom relief in this case.\r\nc) Aveeno\u00ae lotion: Aveeno is an emollient that moisturizes the skin but does not specifically alleviate itching or address the discomfort of a vesicular rash.\r\nd) Dermol\u00ae wash: Dermol is antimicrobial and may help prevent infection, but it is not typically used to relieve itching in vesicular rashes.\r\ne) Diprobase\u00ae cream: While Diprobase provides hydration, it lacks the soothing and anti-itch properties necessary for managing this type of rash.\r\nf) Eumovate\u00ae cream: Eumovate is a moderate-potency corticosteroid that would be too strong for a child of this age without medical supervision. Corticosteroids are not generally recommended for young children without a prescription, especially on facial areas.\r\ng) Hydrocortisone 1% cream: Hydrocortisone is a mild steroid but is typically used in children over 10 years old and only for conditions where inflammation is the primary concern. It is not usually recommended as a first-line treatment for vesicular rashes in young children without a doctor\u2019s approval.\r\nh) Oilatum\u00ae Junior Bath Additive: Oilatum is helpful for maintaining skin hydration and reducing dryness but does not specifically address itching or provide immediate relief for vesicular rash symptoms.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor vesicular rashes in young children, NICE guidelines emphasize gentle, soothing treatments that provide itch relief and avoid unnecessary use of corticosteroids or other strong treatments. Calamine is commonly used due to its cooling and drying effects, which are helpful in managing mild skin conditions in children. Parents should monitor for any signs of infection, such as increased redness, swelling, or discharge, as these symptoms may require further medical evaluation. Encouraging children to avoid scratching and maintaining regular skin hygiene can help manage symptoms and promote healing.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
    "resource_image": null,
    "visible": true,
    "is_calculation": false,
