    "id": 2556,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "A podiatrist independent prescriber is considering prescribing a controlled drug for the treatment of organic disease.",
    "text": "**Theme: Controlled drug prescribing**\r\n**Instruction: For each of the scenarios below, select the most appropriate answer option from the list above. Each option may be used once, more than once, or not at all.**",
    "why": "B. Can only prescribe oral diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, and di-hydrocodeine\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPodiatrist independent prescribers are limited in their controlled drug prescribing authority. They are restricted to prescribing oral formulations of diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, and di-hydrocodeine for conditions related to their scope of practice, such as musculoskeletal pain or anxiety associated with podiatric treatment. Other controlled drugs, particularly those beyond Schedule 4, are outside their permitted prescribing range, necessitating a referral to an appropriately qualified prescriber for further treatment.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA. Cannot prescribe controlled drugs in Schedules 2-5\r\nIncorrect. Podiatrist independent prescribers do have some authority, limited to specific Schedule 4 and 5 controlled drugs, within their scope of practice.\r\n\r\nC. Can only prescribe oral diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, di-hydrocodeine, oxycodone, IV and oral morphine, and fentanyl patches\r\nIncorrect. This authority applies to advanced practitioners in fields like palliative care; podiatrists are limited to fewer controlled drugs and cannot prescribe stronger opioids like oxycodone or morphine.\r\n\r\nD. Can prescribe Schedule 2-5 controlled drugs and does not need a standardised form for private prescriptions for Schedules 2 and 3\r\nIncorrect. Podiatrist prescribers cannot prescribe Schedule 2 or Schedule 3 drugs and must adhere to a limited selection of Schedule 4 and 5 drugs.\r\n\r\nE. Can prescribe any controlled drug listed in Schedules 2-5 for the treatment of addiction\r\nIncorrect. Only practitioners licensed to treat addiction, such as specific doctors, may prescribe for addiction treatment. Podiatrists are not permitted to prescribe controlled drugs for addiction treatment.\r\n\r\nF. Schedules 2-5 for any medical condition within their competence, except diamorphine, cocaine, and dipipanone for addiction treatment\r\nIncorrect. Podiatrists have a restricted scope, limited to specific Schedule 4 drugs; they cannot prescribe controlled drugs more broadly.\r\n\r\nG. Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs only\r\nIncorrect. Podiatrists cannot prescribe Schedule 2 or Schedule 3 drugs, as their authority extends only to specific drugs within Schedules 4 and 5.\r\n\r\nH. Schedule 4 and 5 controlled medicines only\r\nPartially correct but incomplete. While podiatrists can prescribe Schedule 4 and 5 controlled drugs, only a limited range is authorised within their professional scope.\r\n\r\nAccording to the MEP, prescribing authority for controlled drugs depends on the practitioner's qualifications and the specific drug schedule. Podiatrist independent prescribers are restricted to a small selection of controlled drugs, specifically oral diazepam, lorazepam, temazepam, and di-hydrocodeine, for use within their scope of practice. These restrictions are designed to ensure that controlled drug use aligns with the practitioner's expertise while maintaining patient safety.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch OTC lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
