    "title": "**Which of the following medications is the most likely cause of medicine induced psoriasis?**",
    "text": "A 45 year old female presents to the pharmacy complaining of thick scaly plaques on her elbows, trunk and knees. Upon examination, you establish the patient has psoriasis. She informs you she has never had this before and it only started since starting a new medication.",
    "why": "Lithium\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nLithium is the most likely cause of medicine-induced psoriasis. It is a well-known trigger that can induce new onset or worsen pre-existing psoriasis. Lithium influences skin cell turnover and immune responses, leading to the formation of thickened, scaly plaques typical of psoriasis. This side effect is associated with the pro-inflammatory effects of lithium, which can disrupt normal skin regeneration processes.\r\n\r\nThe other options are less likely:\r\n\r\nCiclosporin is actually used to treat severe psoriasis due to its immunosuppressive properties.\r\nLosartan, an antihypertensive medication, is not typically linked with inducing psoriasis.\r\nClarithromycin, this antibiotic, is not associated with psoriasis development.\r\nSertraline, an SSRI, is not commonly linked with causing psoriasis, although there are rare reports of dermatological side effects.\r\n\r\n\r\nPsoriasis is a chronic autoimmune condition characterized by accelerated skin cell turnover, resulting in thick, scaly plaques commonly found on the elbows, knees, trunk, and scalp. The condition is often triggered by infections, stress, trauma, and medications, with lithium, beta-blockers, and antimalarial drugs being common medication triggers. According to NICE guidelines, first-line treatments for psoriasis include topical corticosteroids and vitamin D analogues. In more severe cases, systemic therapies such as methotrexate or biologics may be used. It's important to review and discontinue any medications that could be exacerbating or causing psoriasis, where possible.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch OTC lesson chapter 8 (dermatology):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/over-the-counter-medicines-course-otc",
