    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT required to label broken bulk?**",
    "text": "Bulk containers of medicine can be broken down into smaller quantities suitable for dispensing",
    "why": "B) Drug interactions\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis answer is not required for the labelling of broken bulk medicine. While drug interactions are important information for pharmacists to consider, they are not a legal requirement to be included on the label of broken bulk medicines. The legal labelling requirements for broken bulk medicines focus on information directly related to the medicine's identity, safety, and handling, rather than its interactions with other drugs.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Batch reference number \u2013 This is required for broken bulk labelling. The batch number ensures traceability in case of a recall or quality control issues and is part of the legal requirements for labelling.\r\n\r\nC) Expiry date \u2013 This is required for broken bulk labelling. The expiry date ensures that the medicine is used before it becomes ineffective or potentially unsafe.\r\n\r\nD) Name of medicine \u2013 This is required for broken bulk labelling. The name of the medicine is essential for identifying the product, ensuring that it is dispensed and used correctly.\r\n\r\nE) Quantity of medicines \u2013 This is required for broken bulk labelling. The quantity of medicine being dispensed (e.g., number of tablets or volume) must be clearly stated to ensure proper dosing and to comply with labelling regulations.\r\n\r\nUnder UK law, when breaking down bulk containers of medicines into smaller quantities suitable for dispensing, certain label requirements must be followed to ensure the safe and effective use of the medicine. The label must include the name of the medicine, the quantity, the expiry date, the batch reference number, and any relevant handling and storage requirements. Drug interactions are important for clinical consideration but do not need to be included on the label of the broken bulk container. These labelling regulations help ensure that medicines are correctly identified, stored, and used, and that there is traceability in case of any issues with the product.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
