    "bank": "clinicalOtc",
    "title": "**Which of the following medications is most likely to cause a sore throat and require referral?**",
    "text": "A 42 year old male is complaining of a sore throat, he has recently started on a new medication and has been taking it for two weeks. He has tried sore throat lozenges which he bought at his local supermarket but there has been no improvement.",
    "why": "a) Carbimazole\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nCarbimazole is an antithyroid medication used to treat hyperthyroidism. One of its potential side effects is the development of a sore throat, which can occur due to agranulocytosis (a decrease in white blood cells). This condition increases the risk of infections, including throat infections, making it crucial to refer the patient for further evaluation. Given that the patient has been taking this medication for two weeks and has experienced persistent sore throat symptoms despite using over-the-counter lozenges, it is essential to assess for possible complications associated with carbimazole.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nb) Lithium: While lithium can cause various side effects, sore throat is not a common one. Patients on lithium should be monitored for thyroid function, but a sore throat is not typically indicative of a serious adverse effect.\r\nc) Morphine: Morphine can cause dry mouth and throat irritation, but it is less likely to directly cause a sore throat compared to carbimazole. Morphine's side effects generally do not necessitate immediate referral for a sore throat.\r\nd) Ramipril: This ACE inhibitor can lead to a dry cough, which might contribute to throat irritation, but it is not directly associated with causing a sore throat requiring referral.\r\ne) Warfarin: Warfarin is an anticoagulant that can cause bleeding complications but is not commonly associated with a sore throat.\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to NICE guidelines, patients presenting with a sore throat that persists despite symptomatic treatment should be evaluated, particularly if they are on medications known to affect blood cell counts, such as carbimazole. Referral to a healthcare professional is necessary to assess for possible agranulocytosis and to perform a full blood count if indicated. Prompt recognition of side effects from medications can prevent serious complications and ensure appropriate management. Additionally, educating patients about potential side effects and the importance of monitoring for symptoms during new medication initiation is crucial for safe pharmaceutical care.\r\n\r\nFor more information please watch BNF lesson chapter 2 (Respiratory):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/bnf-course",
